{"title_page": "Bridgewater Canal", "text_new": "{{About|the canal in North West England|the canal in Somerset|Bridgwater and Taunton Canal}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox Canal\n  |name                    = Bridgewater Canal\n  |image                   = Worsley packet house closeup large image.jpg\n  |image_size              = 325px\n  |image_caption           = The Packet House at Worsley, on the canal\n  |former_names            = \n  |original_owner          = \n  |engineer                = [[John Gilbert (agent)|John Gilbert]], [[James Brindley]]\n  |other_engineer          = \n  |date_act                = 1759, 1760, 1762, 1766, 1795\n  |date_began              = \n  |date_use                = 1761\n  |date_completed          = 1761\n  |date_extended           = 1762\n  |date_closed             = \n  |date_restored           = \n  |len_ft                     = 72\n  |len_in                  = 0\n  |original_boat_length_ft    = \n  |original_boat_length_in = \n  |len_note                = \n  |beam_ft                    = 14\n  |beam_in                 = 9\n  |original_beam_ft           = \n  |original_beam_in        = \n  |beam_note               = \n  |start_point             = [[Worsley]]\n  |original_start          = \n  |start_note              = \n  |end_point               = [[Runcorn]]\n  |original_end            = [[Manchester]]\n  |end_note                = ''See article''\n  |branch                  = \n  |branch_of               = \n  |connects_to             = [[Rochdale Canal]], [[Trent and Mersey Canal]], [[Leeds and Liverpool Canal]], [[Manchester Ship Canal]]\n  |length_mi                  = 41\n  |locks                   = 0\n  |original_num_locks      = 10 at Runcorn\n  |lock_note               = ''See article''\n  |status                  = Open\n  |navigation_authority    = Manchester Ship Canal Company\n}}\n{{Bridgewater Canal map}}\nThe '''Bridgewater Canal''' connects [[Runcorn]], [[Manchester]] and [[Leigh, Greater Manchester|Leigh]], in [[North West England]]. It was commissioned by [[Francis Egerton, 3rd Duke of Bridgewater]], to transport coal from his mines in [[Worsley]] to Manchester. It was opened in 1761 from Worsley to Manchester, and later extended from Manchester to Runcorn, and then from Worsley to Leigh.\n\nThe [[canal]] is connected to the [[Manchester Ship Canal]] via a lock at Cornbrook; to the [[Rochdale Canal]] in Manchester; to the [[Trent and Mersey Canal]] at [[Preston Brook]], southeast of Runcorn; and to the [[Leeds and Liverpool Canal]] at Leigh. It once connected with the [[River Mersey]] at Runcorn but has since been cut off by a slip road to the [[Silver Jubilee Bridge]].\n\nFollowing the construction of the [[Sankey Brook Navigation]], Bridgewater has been argued to be the first true canal of the [[Industrial Revolution]] in England, and it required the construction of an [[navigable aqueduct|aqueduct]] to cross the [[River Irwell]], one of the first of its kind. Its success helped inspire a period of intense canal building in Britain, known as [[Canal Mania]]. It later faced intense competition from the [[Liverpool and Manchester Railway]] and the [[Macclesfield Canal]]. Navigable throughout its history, it is one of the few canals in Britain not to have been nationalised, and remains privately owned. Pleasure craft now use the canal which forms part of the [[Cheshire Ring]] network of canals.\n\n== Design and construction ==\n[[Francis Egerton, 3rd Duke of Bridgewater]], owned some of the coal mines dug to supply [[North West England]] with fuel for the [[steam engine]]s instrumental in powering England's [[Industrial Revolution]].<ref name=pb15>{{Harvnb|Parkinson-Bailey|2000|p=15}}</ref><ref name=chal34>{{Harvnb|Chaloner|1963|p=34}}</ref>  The duke transported his coal along the [[Mersey and Irwell Navigation]] and also by [[packhorse]], but each method was inefficient and expensive; river transport was subject to the vagaries of river navigation,<ref>Vessels were affected by tide levels, and the shared use of water by industry</ref> and the amount of coal packhorses could carry was limited by its relative weight.{{sfn|Kindleberger|1993|p=192|ps=}}  The duke's underground mines also suffered from persistent flooding, caused by the [[geology]] of the Middle [[Coal Measures]], where the [[Worsley Four Foot mine|coal seam]] lies beneath a layer of permeable [[sandstone]].\n\nHaving visited the [[Canal du Midi]] in France and watched the construction of the [[Sankey Canal]] in England,<ref name=Penninewaterways>{{cite web |title=History of the Bridgewater Canal |url=http://www.penninewaterways.co.uk/bridgewater/bri2.htm |publisher=Pennine Waterways |accessdate=14 August 2008}}</ref> the duke's solution to these problems was to build an underground canal at Worsley, connected to a surface canal between [[Worsley]] and [[Salford, Greater Manchester|Salford]].<ref name=\"Priestleyp89\">{{Harvnb|Priestley|1831|p=89}}</ref>  In addition to easing overland transport difficulties and providing drainage for his mines, an underground canal would provide a reliable source of water for the surface canal, and also eliminate the need to lift the coal to the surface (an expensive and difficult proposition). The canal boats would carry {{convert|30|LT}} at a time, pulled by only one horse&nbsp;\u2013 more than ten times the amount of cargo per horse that was possible with a cart.{{sfn|N/A|1978|p=990|ps=}}  The duke and his estate manager [[John Gilbert (agent)|John Gilbert]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Coal and Water&nbsp;\u2014 The Bridgewater Canal, John Gilbert |url=http://www.peak41.co.uk/coalandwater/johngilbert.html |publisher=Mike Higginbottom |accessdate=14 August 2008|format= \u2013 <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=intitle%3ACoal+and+Water%26nbsp%3B%E2%80%94+The+Bridgewater+Canal%2C+John+Gilbert&as_publication=&as_ylo=&as_yhi=&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup> |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070718221904/http://www.peak41.co.uk/coalandwater/johngilbert.html |archivedate=18 July 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref> produced a plan of the canal, and in 1759 obtained an [[Acts of Parliament in the United Kingdom|Act of Parliament]], enabling its construction.<ref name=\"Priestleyp89\"/><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/a2a/records.aspx?cat=129-bw |title=Bridgewater Estates Collection |publisher=The National Archives |accessdate=23 June 2013}}</ref>{{efn|An Act to enable the most noble Francis Duke of Bridgewater, to make a navigable cut or canal from a certain place in the township of Salford, to or near Worsley Mill, and Middlewood, in the manor of Worsley, and to or near a place called Hollin Ferry, in the county palatine of Lancaster. 32nd George II.}}\n\n[[James Brindley]] was brought in for his technical expertise (having previously installed a pumping system at the nearby [[Wet Earth Colliery]]), and after a six-day visit suggested varying the route of the proposed canal away from Salford, instead taking it across the [[River Irwell]] to [[Stretford]] and thereon into Manchester.<ref name=\"Skemptonp76\">{{Harvnb|Skempton|2002|p=76}}</ref>  This route would make connecting to any future canals much easier, and would also increase competition with the Mersey and Irwell Navigation company.<ref name=\"Ref-1\">Boughey, Joseph. (1998) Hadfield's British Canals, Sutton Publishing, {{ISBN|0-7509-1840-3}}</ref>{{sfn|Mather|1970|p=xvi|ps=}}  Brindley moved into [[Worsley Old Hall]] and spent 46&nbsp;days surveying the proposed route, which to cross the Irwell would require the construction of an aqueduct at [[Barton-upon-Irwell]].<ref name=chal34/>  At the duke's behest, in January 1760 Brindley also travelled to London to give evidence before a [[parliamentary committee]].  The duke therefore gained a second Act of Parliament, which superseded the original.<ref name=\"Priestleyp89\"/><ref name=\"Skemptonp76\"/>{{efn|An Act to enable the most noble Francis Duke of Bridgewater, to make a navigable cut or canal from a certain place in the township of Salford, over the Irwell, to the town of Manchester, in the county palatine of Lancaster, and to or near Longford Bridge, in the township of Stretford, in the said county.}}\n\nBrindley's planned route began at Worsley and passed southeast through [[Eccles, Greater Manchester|Eccles]], before turning south to cross the River Irwell on the [[Barton Aqueduct]]. From there it continued southeast along the edge of [[Trafford Park]], and then east into Manchester. Although a connection with the Mersey and Irwell Navigation was included in the new Act, at Hulme Locks in [[Castlefield]] (on land previously occupied by [[Hulme Hall, Hulme|Hulme Hall]]), this was not completed until 1838. The terminus would be at Castlefield Basin, where the nearby [[River Medlock]] was to help supply the canal with water.<ref>{{cite web |title=Salford Hundred, Ancestry, Annals and History |url=http://www.mancuniensis.info/WorsleyFPX.htm |publisher=Elaine and Roger Hart, Bolton, Greater Manchester |accessdate=14 August 2008}}</ref>  Boats would unload their cargoes inside the duke's purpose-built warehouse.  There were no locks in Brindley's design, demonstrating{{clarify|whose opinion?|date=January 2011}} his ability as a competent engineer.<ref name=\"Skemptonp76\"/>  The Barton Aqueduct was built relatively quickly for the time; work commenced in September 1760 and the first boat crossed on 17&nbsp;July 1761.{{sfn|Collins|1812|p=213|ps=}}\n\n[[File:BrownManchesterMuralBridgewater.jpg|right|thumb|''The Opening of the Bridgewater Canal A.D. 1761'' by [[Ford Madox Brown]], one of ''[[The Manchester Murals]]'' at [[Manchester Town Hall]]]]\n[[File:Bridgewater Canal at Barton 1891.jpg|right|thumb|Brindley's aqueduct, replaced late in the 19th century]]\nThe duke invested a large sum of money in the scheme. From Worsley to Manchester its construction cost \u00a3168,000 (equivalent to \u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|168000|1761|r=-1}}}} in {{Inflation-year|UK}}),{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}{{sfn|Timbs|1860|p=363|ps=}} but its advantages over land and river transport meant that within a year of its opening in 1761, the price of coal in Manchester fell by about half.<ref name=Bridgewatercollieries>{{citation |title=The Times newspaper: Bridgewater Collieries |url=http://archive.timesonline.co.uk/tol/viewArticle.arc?toDate=1985-12-31&fromDate=1785-01-01&currentPageNumber=1&resultsPerPage=10&sortBy=default&offset=0&viewName=&addFilters=&removeFilters=&addCat=&queryKeywords=bridgewater+canal&sectionId=1040&currPgSmartSet=1&pageId=ARCHIVE-The_Times-1913-12-01-08&articleId=ARCHIVE-The_Times-1913-12-01-08-001&xmlpath=&pubId=17&totalResults=1638&addRefineFilters=&removeRefineFilters=&addRefineCat=&next_Page=false&prev_Page=false&date_dd_From=1&date_mm_From=01&date_yyyy_From=1785&date_dd_to_range=31&date_mm_to_range=12&date_yyyy_to_range=1985&date_dd_from_precise=1&date_mm_from_precise=01&date_yyyy_from_precise=1785&isDateSearch=false&dateSearchType=range&refineQuerykeywordText= |date=1 December 1913 |accessdate=19 July 2008 |location=London |first1=Rachel |last1=Sylvester |first2=Sam |last2=Coates}}</ref>  This success helped inspire a period of intense canal building, known as [[Canal Mania]].{{sfn|Kindleberger|1993|pp=192\u2013193|ps=}} Along with its stone aqueduct at Barton-upon-Irwell, the Bridgewater Canal was considered a major engineering achievement. One commentator wrote that when finished, \"[the canal] will be the most extraordinary thing in the Kingdom, if not in Europe. The boats in some places are to go underground, and in other places over a navigable river, without communicating with its waters\".<ref name=\"Ref-1\"/>\n\nIn addition to the duke's warehouse at Manchester, more buildings were built by Brindley and extended to Alport Street (now called [[Deansgate]]).<ref name=pb15/>  The warehouses were of timber-frame design, with load-bearing hand-made brick walls, supported on cast iron posts. The duke's warehouse was badly damaged by fire in 1789 but was rebuilt.<ref name=pb15/><ref name=pb17>{{Harvnb|Parkinson-Bailey|2000|p=17}}</ref>\n[[File:Bridgewater foundary.gif|thumb|right|Bridgewater Foundry at Patricroft, 1839]]\n\n=== Manchester to Runcorn extension ===\nIn September 1761, with his assistant Hugh Oldham,{{sfn|Skempton|2002|p=79|ps=}} Brindley surveyed an extension from Longford Bridge to Hempstones, near [[Halton, Cheshire]].<ref name=\"Skemptonp76\"/>  He assisted in obtaining Parliamentary approval for the Bridgewater Canal Extension Act of 1762<ref>An Act to enable the most noble Francis Duke of Bridgewater, to make a navigable cut or canal from Longford Bridge, in the township of Stretford, in the county palatine of Lancaster, to the River Mersey, at a place called the Hempstones, in the township of Halton, in the county of Chester.</ref> which allowed the construction of an extension to the canal, from Manchester, to the River Mersey at [[Runcorn]].<ref name=chal35>{{Harvnb|Chaloner|1963|p=35}}</ref>  Despite objections from the Mersey and Irwell Navigation Company,<ref name=\"Skemptonp76\"/> [[Royal assent]] was given on 24&nbsp;March 1762.<ref name=anon29>{{Harvnb|Anon|p=29}}</ref>  A junction, Waters Meeting, was created in [[Trafford Park]], at which the new extension branched south through [[Stretford]], [[Sale, Greater Manchester|Sale]], [[Altrincham]], [[Lymm]] and finally to [[Runcorn]].\n\nIn December 1761 Brindley undertook a survey of the route at Runcorn. His initial plan was to make the terminus at Hempstones, east of Runcorn Gap,<!-- where the Mersey narrows between the town of Runcorn and a promontory which was to later form part of the town of [[Widnes]] - not certain this is relevant so will leave hidden for now--> but following a study of the tides and depth of water there, he decided instead to build the terminus west of Runcorn Gap.{{sfn|Starkey|1990|p=125|ps=}}  This change was designed to accommodate [[Mersey Flat|Mersey flats]], although the low fixed bridges required that traffic on the canal be able to lower or unship their masts.<ref name=st13>{{Harvnb|Starkey|1983|p=13}}</ref>  Runcorn basin was almost {{convert|90|ft|m|0}} above the Mersey,{{sfn|Nickson|1887|p=159|ps=}} so a flight of ten locks, described as \"the wonder of their time\",{{sfn|Starkey|1990|p=127|ps=}} was built to connect the two.  Nine locks had a fall of {{convert|2|m|ft|0}}, with a fall at the river lock of more than {{convert|6|m|ft|0}} at low water. It allowed vessels to enter and leave the canal on any [[tide]]. The connection to the Mersey was made on 1&nbsp;January 1773.<ref name=st126/>  The river's tidal action tended to deposit [[silt]] around the lower entrance to the locks, so to counteract this a channel, equipped with gates at each end and known as the Duke's Gut, was cut through the marshes upriver from the locks.  At high tide the gates were closed, and with the ebb of the tide were opened to release water, which scoured the silt from the entrance to the locks.  The cut created an island, known as Runcorn Island, crossed by Castle Bridge.{{sfn|1970|p=20}}{{sfn|Starkey|1990|pp=128\u2013129|ps=}}<ref>It was known as Castle Bridge because it made a connection with a rocky promontory which had once been the site of a castle built by [[Ethelfleda]] to defend her kingdom of [[Mercia]] from [[Viking]] invasion.</ref>\n\n[[File:Stretford.jpg|thumb|left|Ordnance Survey map of 1843 showing the canal crossing the River Mersey at Barfoot Bridge, Stretford]]\n[[File:Runcorn soapworks.jpg|left|thumb|The canal at Runcorn between the factories]]\n[[File:OS One-inch Sheet 100 Extract Runcorn Bridgewater Canal 1966.jpg|left|thumb|Extract from OS one-inch sheet 100 showing the junction between the Bridgewater Canal and the Manchester Ship Canal at Runcorn, with the flight of locks, as it was in 1966]]\nThe connection to Manchester was delayed by [[Brooke baronets|Sir Richard Brooke]] of [[Norton Priory]]. Concerned that boatmen might poach his game and wildfowl, Brooke did not want the canal to pass through his land. The Act included several stipulations: the canal should not come within {{convert|325|m|ft|0}} of his house; the towpath should be on the south side of the canal, furthest away from Brooke's house; there should be no quays, buildings, hedges or fences to obstruct the view; no vessels were to be moored within {{convert|1000|m|ft|0}} of the house, other than during construction.  Eventually, though, a compromise was reached.  This included the construction of a link to the [[Trent and Mersey Canal]] at [[Preston Brook]] (permitted by the Trent and Mersey Canal Act of 1766),{{sfn|Priestley|1831|p=90|ps=}} and the building of the canal's terminus to the west of Runcorn Gap.<ref name=st126/>  The Trent and Mersey link gave the Duke access to the Midlands, and forestalled the Weaver Trustees from making their own junction with the canal.{{sfn|Mather|1970|pp=xvi\u2013xvii|ps=}} The new extension also met with opposition from the Mersey and Irwell Navigation, until the duke purchased a controlling interest in the company.<ref name=chal35/>  The first part of the new extension was opened in 1767,<ref name=\"Chalonerp36\">{{Harvnb|Chaloner|1963|p=36}}</ref> and completed in full by March 1776,<ref name=st126>{{Harvnb|Starkey|1990|p=126}}</ref> but Brindley did not live to see its completion; it was continued by his brother-in-law, [[Hugh Henshall]].<ref name=anon29/>\n\nThe total cost of the canal, from Worsley to Manchester and from Longford Bridge to the Mersey at Runcorn, was \u00a3220,000.{{sfn|Nickson|1887|p=161|ps=}}  Alongside the Mersey, the duke built [[Port of Runcorn|Runcorn Dock]], several warehouses, and [[Bridgewater House, Runcorn|Bridgewater House]], a temporary home from which he could supervise operations at the Runcorn end.  Two locks up from the tideway was a small [[dry dock]].<ref name=st13/>\n\n=== Sale to Stockport branch ===\nIn 1766 the Duke gained a fourth act of parliament for a branch canal between [[Sale, Greater Manchester|Sale Moor]] and [[Stockport]] which was to follow the valley of the Mersey.  The Act was applied for to counter a proposed canal that would give the towns of [[Stockport]] and [[Macclesfield]] access to the Mersey, via the [[River Weaver]].<ref name=\"Chalonerp36\"/>  The work was not done, the Act lapsed and this section of canal was never built.<ref>{{citation|title=1765 - From Sale to Stockport|url=http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/timeline5.html|publisher=The Manchester Ship Canal Company|accessdate=14 August 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121224755/http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/timeline5.html|archivedate=21 November 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOver two decades later, the nearby [[Manchester Bolton & Bury Canal]] had sought a connection to other waterways, and it appears that the Duke had planned to limit the activities of the new company.  On 15 December 1792 the Duke purchased a portion of the [[Ringspiggot]] estate in Salford which blocked the MB&BC's plans to build a riverside basin and wharfs there.<ref name=\"Tomlinsonp33\">{{Harvnb|Tomlinson|1991|p=33}}</ref>\n\n=== Worsley to Leigh extension ===\nIn 1795 the duke secured a fifth Act which enabled him to extend the canal a further {{convert|5|mi|km|0}} from Worsley via [[Boothstown]], [[Astley, Greater Manchester|Astley Green]] and [[Bedford, Greater Manchester|Bedford]] to Leigh.<ref>{{cite web |title=1795 \u2013 From Worsley to Leigh |url=http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/timeline6.html |publisher=The Manchester Ship Canal Company |accessdate=14 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121225106/http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/timeline6.html |archivedate=21 November 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=chal37>{{Harvnb|Chaloner|1963|p=37}}</ref>  The new extension enabled the supply to Manchester of coal from Leigh and the surrounding districts.{{sfn|Smiles|2006|p=272|ps=}}  On 21 June 1819 an Act of Parliament was enacted to create a link between this extension and the [[Leeds and Liverpool Canal]] at [[Wigan]].{{sfn|Tomlinson|1991|p=44|ps=}}\n\nAccess to the canal brought about a rapid development in coal mining on the [[Manchester Coalfield]] west of Worsley. Chaddock pits in the east of Tyldesley were connected to an underground level from Worsley. In 1820, to ease congestion at the Delph in Worsley, Chaddock Pit was connected to the canal at Boothstown basin by an underground canal, the Chaddock Level which ran in a north west direction from the canal at Boothstown to the pit.{{sfn|Hayes|2004|pp=31\u201332|ps=}} Sometime after 1840 Samuel Jackson built a narrow gauge tramroad worked by horses from his [[Astley and Tyldesley Collieries|Gin Pit Colliery]] to Marsland Green where he installed cranes and tipplers to load barges at a wharf. The tramroad was later worked by locomotives.{{sfn|Hayes|2004|p=148|ps=}} In 1867 the [[Fletcher, Burrows and Company|Fletchers]] built a private railway line and the Bedford Basin with facilities for loading coal from [[Howe Bridge]] onto barges. [[Astley Green Colliery]] began winding coal on the north bank of the canal in 1912. In the 1940s and '50s coal was sent to [[Barton Power Station]] and Runcorn Gas Works.{{sfn|Sweeney|1997|p=332|ps=}}\n\n=== Connection to Rochdale Canal ===\n[[File:Map of Manchester 1801.PNG|thumb|right|A map from 1801 showing the Bridgewater and Rochdale canals yet to be connected]]\n[[File:Packet House Worsley.jpg|right|thumb|The Packet House at Worsley, in 1866]]\n[[File:Bridgewater letter 1837.jpg|thumb|right|portrait|Letter to the Bridgewater Canal offices concerning wives sleeping on boats, dated 11&nbsp;November 1837]]\nUpon completion of the [[Rochdale Canal]] in 1804, the two canals were joined at Castlefield.<ref name=pb17/>{{sfn|Pickering|1807|p=663|ps=}}  This connection may have been a factor in the failure of the Manchester Bolton & Bury Canal Company's rival scheme to build a canal between [[Bury, Greater Manchester|Bury]] and Sladen.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1991|pp=34\u201335|ps=}}  The River Medlock, a major source of water for the canal and which was almost as badly polluted as the nearby Irwell, was diverted through a tunnel under the canal at Castlefield by [[Charles Edward Cawley]], a civil engineer for the [[County Borough of Salford|Salford Corporation]] and later [[Member of Parliament#United Kingdom|MP]] for Salford.  The canal was from that point supplied by the much purer water of the Rochdale Canal.{{sfn|Corbett|1974|p=41|ps=}}\n\n=== Mines ===\n{{Main|Worsley Navigable Levels}}\nWorsley Delph, in Worsley, originally a centuries-old [[sandstone]] [[quarry]] near Worsley Brook, was the entrance to the Navigable Levels. It is now a [[Scheduled Monument]].<ref>{{Cite PastScape |num=44278 |desc=Worsley Delph |access-date=30 December 2007 |mode=cs2}}</ref>  Two entrances, built years apart, allow access to the specially built M-boats (also known as [[Starvationers]]), the largest of which could carry {{convert|12|LT}} of coal. Inside the mines {{convert|46|mi|km|0}} of underground canal on four levels, linked by inclined planes, were constructed. The mines ceased production in 1887.<ref name=BLW11>Ware (1989), p.&nbsp;11.</ref>  As the canal passes through Worsley, [[iron oxide]] from the mines has, for many years, stained the water bright orange. The removal of this colouration is currently the subject of a \u00a32.5&nbsp;million remedial scheme.<ref>{{cite web |title=Transformation of Worsley's Orange Canal |url=http://www.coal.gov.uk/media//94807/Page%208%20and%209%20Enviro%20Issue%2013.pdf |format=pdf |accessdate=15 July 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327152417/http://www.coal.gov.uk/media//94807/Page%208%20and%209%20Enviro%20Issue%2013.pdf |archive-date=27 March 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Traffic ===\nIn 1791 the mines at Worsley produced {{convert|100282|LT}} of coal, {{convert|60461|LT}} of which were \"sold down the navigation\";<ref name=chal37/> {{convert|12000|LT}} of [[Halite|rocksalt]] was also transported from [[Cheshire]].  Sales of coal were \u00a319,455, and nearly \u00a330,000 was earned from other cargoes.  Passenger traffic in 1791 brought in receipts of \u00a33,781.<ref name=chal37/>\n\nThe canal also carried passengers and was in keen competition with the Mersey and Irwell Navigation Company (M&IN).  The journey down river by the latter route took eight hours (nine hours in the up direction) while the journey on the Bridgewater canal took nine hours each way.  Fares were similar but the Bridgewater route was said to be \"more picturesque\".{{sfn|Starkey|1990|p=130|ps=}} [[Boating]] men also used the canal.  They lifted their small lightweight boats out of the M&IN at Runcorn, and carried them a short distance up the steep streets onto the Bridgewater Canal.{{sfn|Corbett|1974|p=40|ps=}}\n\nBarges on the canal continued to be towed by horses until the middle of the 19th century, when they were replaced by steam-powered boats after a fatal epidemic spread through the horse population. The \"dense smoke\" produced by the steam barges and their \"harsh unnecessary whistling\" proved unpopular with some local residents, who also began to suffer from a condition known as canal throat, \"no doubt caused by the foul emanations given off by its [the Bridgewater Canal's] horribly filthy water\".<ref name=AspinP48>{{Harvnb|Aspin|1995|p=48}}</ref>\n\nThe canal carried commercial freight traffic until 1975; the last regular cargo was grain from Liverpool to Manchester for BOCM. It is now used mainly by pleasure craft and hosts two [[sport rowing|rowing]] clubs&nbsp;\u2013 Trafford Rowing Club and Manchester University Boat Club.\n\n== Bridgewater Trustees ==\nThe Duke of Bridgewater died on 8 March 1803.  By his will the income from the canal was to be paid to his nephew [[George Leveson-Gower, 1st Duke of Sutherland|George Leveson-Gower]], the Marquess of Stafford (later the 1st Duke of Sutherland).  On his death it was to go to Stafford's second son [[Francis Egerton, 1st Earl of Ellesmere|Francis]], provided he changed his name to Egerton; and then to his heirs and successors. The management of the company was placed in the hands of three trustees.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=xviii\u2013xix}}</ref> These were [[Archibald Macdonald|Sir Archibald Macdonald]], who was [[Lord Chief Baron of the Exchequer]], [[Edward Venables-Vernon-Harcourt]], at the time the [[Bishop of Carlisle]] and later the [[Archbishop of York]], and, as Superintendent, [[Robert Haldane Bradshaw]], the Duke's agent. Bradshaw managed the estate, for which he received a salary of \u00a32,000 a year and the use of the duke's mansions at Worsley and Runcorn. The other two trustees had each married nieces of the duke and were \"dummy trustees\".<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|p=6}}</ref>\n[[File:BridgewaterCanalTradeFigures.png|left|thumb|400px|Value of trade carried on the Bridgewater Canal 1806\u201371<ref name=mather358>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=358\u2013359}}</ref>]]\nDuring the time the canal was administered by the Bridgewater Trustees, it made a profit every year.<ref name=mather358/>  Until his retirement in 1834, the administration was carried out entirely by Bradshaw. It has been calculated that the average annual profit between 1806 and 1826 was of the order of 13 per cent, and in 1824, the best year, it was 23 per cent.{{sfn|Mather|1970|p=7|ps=}}  Bradshaw found it difficult to delegate, and complained of being over-worked, but he was also regarded as being a \"formidable bargainer\".{{sfn|Mather|1970|pp=10\u201311|ps=}} In 1805 he was approached by the proprietors of the nearby [[Manchester Bolton & Bury Canal]] to resolve a dispute with a Salford landowner, but his response was delayed.<ref name=\"Tomlinsonp33\"/> In 1810 there was a general agreement with the [[Mersey and Irwell Navigation]] Company (M&IN) to simultaneously raise freight charges. However any cooperation between the two companies was short-lived and by 1812 the Mersey and Irwell had reduced their charges. Further competition was to come from other carriers who used the canal; in 1824 the traffic carried by private companies exceeded that carried by the Trustees for the first time. However, in time more profit came from \"tonnage traffic\" (that carried by private companies) than from the Bridgewater's own carriage of freight.{{sfn|Mather|1970|pp=12\u201315|ps=}} Bradshaw's administration saw increased deterioration of the fabric of the canal, the locks, docks and warehouses. The undertakings were starved of capital largely owing to inadequate provision for it in the duke's will.{{sfnp|Mather|1970|pp=21\u201323|ps=}} There were also problems caused by silting around the entrance to the Mersey and by the changing channels of the river itself.{{sfn|Mather|1970|pp=17, 20|ps=}}\n\nDuring the 1820s there was increased dissatisfaction with the canals. They did not cope well with increasing volumes of cargo, and they were perceived as monopolistic, and the preserve of the landed gentry class.  There was increased interest in the possibility of railway construction.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=27\u201333}}</ref>  The possible construction of a railway between Liverpool and Manchester was vigorously opposed by Bradshaw, who refused railway surveyors access to land owned by the Trustees.  When the first [[Bill (proposed law)|bill]] was presented to parliament in 1825, the Trustees opposed and it was overthrown.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=36\u201337}}</ref> However, later in the year Lord Stafford, possibly persuaded to do so by [[William Huskisson]], invested \u00a3100,000 (one-fifth of the required capital), in the [[Liverpool and Manchester Railway]].  Following this the Trustees withdrew their opposition to the construction of the railway; they did not petition against the second bill, which was passed in 1826.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=38\u201341}}</ref> At the same time as he made his investment in the railway, Lord Stafford advanced \u00a340,000 for improvements to the canal. This was spent mainly on a second line of locks at Runcorn, which were completed in 1828, plus new warehouses at Manchester and Liverpool.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=54\u201355}}</ref>  The additional line of locks cost \u00a335,000<ref name=\"Starkeyp179\">{{Harvnb|Starkey|1990|p=179}}</ref> and was used for traffic heading to Manchester, while the old line was used for traffic passing down to the Mersey.<ref>{{Harvnb|Starkey|1983|p=173}}</ref>\n\nIn 1830 the new railway opened and by the end of the year was carrying freight. Bradshaw immediately went into competition by lowering the rates of carriage on the canal and by offering improved terms to the private carriers. By so doing he managed to maintain the volume of traffic carried by the canal, both freight and passengers, at a time when the country was suffering a trade [[Depression (economics)|depression]]. However Bradshaw's tactics led to a sharp decline in profits. At the same time costs were rising, partly due to the use of steamboats on the Mersey. Further competition came with the opening of the [[Macclesfield Canal]] in 1831 which gave separate access to Manchester from the Midlands.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=57\u201361}}</ref> In November 1831 Bradshaw suffered a [[stroke]], as a result of which he lost the use of his left arm and leg, and there is evidence that it also impaired his judgement.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=80\u201382, 85}}</ref>\n\nMatters came to a head in 1833, the year in which the canal made its lowest profit since the death of the Duke.<ref name=mather358/> On 19&nbsp;July the Marquess of Stafford (now the 1st Duke of Sutherland) died and the profits from the canal passed to Francis Egerton. On 25&nbsp;September Bradshaw's son, [[James Bradshaw (MP for Brackley)|Captain James Bradshaw]], who had been acting as a deputy superintendent to the Trustees, and who had been expected to succeed his father as Superintendent, committed suicide. The agent for both Francis Egerton and his older brother, who was now the [[George Sutherland-Leveson-Gower, 2nd Duke of Sutherland|2nd Duke of Sutherland]], was [[James Loch]].<ref name=mather84>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=84\u201386}}</ref>  The events that followed were \"stage-managed by Loch\".<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|p=85}}</ref> He reported to Francis Egerton that Bradshaw was no longer fit to be Superintendent, and then persuaded Bradshaw to retire on his full salary. It had been expected that he would appoint his other son, William Rigby Bradshaw, as his successor, but Loch persuaded him to appoint James Sothern in the position; Sothern had been the principal agent of the Trust since December 1832. He took over the position of Superintendent on 3&nbsp;February 1834.<ref name=mather84/>  The appointment of Sothern was not a success. Charges were made against him of dishonesty and of nepotism. He entered into disputes and disagreements with Loch, with Francis Egerton, and with the other two trustees. (Sir Archibald Macdonald had died in 1826; by this time his place had been taken by the [[William Courtenay, 10th Earl of Devon|10th Earl of Devon]]). To avoid a costly lawsuit, at the end of 1836 Sothern agreed to retire on various conditions which included receipt of \u00a345,000. On 1&nbsp;March 1837, he was succeeded as Superintendent by James Loch.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=87\u201397}}</ref>\n\nLoch was extremely busy and did not have time to deal with the detailed administration of the Trust. He therefore looked for a deputy to take on these duties. His first choice was Richard Smith who was the mine agent to the Trustees of the [[John Ward, 1st Earl of Dudley|1st Earl of Dudley]]. However this was perceived as poaching and it led to such controversy that Smith declined the offer and recommended his son, [[George Samuel Fereday Smith]] for the post. Fereday Smith was appointed as Deputy Superintendent in March 1837 on a salary of \u00a3600 a year, half of the salary which had been offered to his father.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=98\u201399}}</ref> Loch immediately undertook a reorganisation of the administration and efficiency of the business,<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=100\u2013102}}</ref> restored the agreement with the Old Quay Company to raise freight charges, and improved the facilities for passengers, including the introduction of \"swift boats\".<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=105\u2013110}}</ref>  By 1837, the Trustees employed around 3,000&nbsp;people (including those working in the colliery and in Worsley Yard), making it one of the largest employers in the country at the time.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=1\u20132}}</ref> Since the death of the Duke the amount of freight carried by the canal had almost trebled; in 1803 it carried {{convert|334495|LT}} of goods and in 1836 {{convert|968795|LT}}.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|p=3}}</ref>\n\nIn 1843 a new dock, the Francis Dock, was opened at Runcorn.<ref name=\"Starkeyp179\"/> The late 1830s and early 1840s had seen increased competition between the Bridgewater Canal on the one hand, and other canal companies and the railways on the other.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=121\u2013151}}</ref> The most dangerous of the rivals was the Mersey and Irwell Navigation Company who started to reduce their rates again in 1840. This led to a price war between the two canal companies and the Liverpool and Manchester Railway, who had previously cooperated on rates.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=152\u2013155}}</ref>  Eventually, in desperation, the Bridgewater Trustees bought the Mersey and Irwell and took over its ownership on 1 January 1844.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=162\u2013163}}</ref> During the same year competition with other canals was further reduced by agreements made with the [[Ellesmere Canal|Ellesmere and Chester Canal]] Company and with the Anderton Carrying Company.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=167\u2013169}}</ref>  In 1844 the canal made a profit of \u00a376,410, the second highest during the time it was administered by the Trustees.<ref name=mather358/>\n\nHaving seen off competition from other canal companies, the next major threat was to come from the railways.  This was the period in the mid-1840s known as the [[Railway Mania]].  The railways competed with the canals in three ways; by building, or threatening to build, new lines which would be in direct competition with the canals; by amalgamation into giant companies (such as the [[Midland Railway|Midland]] and the [[London and North Western Railway|London and North Western]] companies), which gave them more political power; and by taking over ownership of canal companies.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=176\u2013180}}</ref>  On 13&nbsp;April 1844 ''[[The Times]]'' newspaper reported that the canal was to be emptied of water, and converted into a railway,<ref>{{Citation |title=The Times newspaper: The Bridgewater Canal | url=http://archive.timesonline.co.uk/tol/viewArticle.arc?toDate=1985-12-31&fromDate=1785-01-01&currentPageNumber=1&resultsPerPage=10&sortBy=default&offset=0&viewName=&addFilters=&removeFilters=&addCat=&queryKeywords=bridgewater+canal&sectionId=1040&currPgSmartSet=1&pageId=ARCHIVE-The_Times-1844-04-13-08&articleId=ARCHIVE-The_Times-1844-04-13-08-015&xmlpath=&pubId=17&totalResults=1638&addRefineFilters=&removeRefineFilters=&addRefineCat=&next_Page=false&prev_Page=false&date_dd_From=1&date_mm_From=01&date_yyyy_From=1785&date_dd_to_range=31&date_mm_to_range=12&date_yyyy_to_range=1985&date_dd_from_precise=1&date_mm_from_precise=01&date_yyyy_from_precise=1785&isDateSearch=false&dateSearchType=range&refineQuerykeywordText= |date=13 April 1844|accessdate=19 July 2008 | location=London |first1=Rachel |last1=Sylvester |first2=Sam |last2=Coates}}</ref> although nothing came of this scheme. In 1845, in return for concessions, the Trustees supported the [[Grand Junction Railway]] in its campaign to build a more direct line to Liverpool, which crossed the Mersey over a bridge at Runcorn Gap.  However the bill was overthrown in the House of Lords.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=182\u2013183}}</ref>  Competition from the railways and other canals led to a decline in the trading and the profits between 1845 and 1848, but there was no \"disastrous collapse\".<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|p=189}}</ref>  During this time the Trustees and their representatives were engaged in vigorous campaigns in Parliament to protect their interests.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=185\u2013189}}</ref>\n\nBy October 1844 a bonding warehouse had been built in Manchester and the first cargo to arrive was announced in a letter to the ''[[Manchester Guardian]],'' later printed in ''[[The Times]]:''\n{{quote|<center>FIRST ARRIVAL IN THE PORT OF MANCHESTER OF A CARGO OF GOODS FOR BOND</center>\nWe have great pleasure in recording the first arrival in the Port of Manchester of a vessel, with an entire cargo of wines and spirits removed in bond, and for bonding in Manchester. The vessel, a flat named the Express, was wholly laden with a valuable cargo of wines and spirits, in all about 40 tons weight, belonging to Mr. William Gibb, spirit merchant, of this town, whose active and long-continued exertions in the struggle to obtain the privilege of bonding for this great and important borough are about to be acknowledged in the form of a substantial mark of respect and gratitude by his fellow-townsmen. The Express arrived from Liverpool on Saturday evening; but it was yesterday morning before she began to unload. She is lying in the Bridgewater Canal, Knott Mill where the Duke's trustees have constructed a large bonding vault, which Mr. Gibb has taken and had licensed for the purpose, and we believe he is now removing his stock of wine and spirits from other ports to Manchester, for the greater convenience of sampling and sale. The lockers, gaugers, and other officers of Customs were in attendance, superintending the unloading of the vessel and thus have commenced the operations of the Manchester Custom-house. It is a gratifying circumstance that a gentleman who took so prominent a part in the struggle to obtain the boon of bonding for Manchester should be the first to enjoy the fruits of its success. We hope ere long to record the general operation of the system; though it will require a little time, perhaps, as it must have a beginning. -&nbsp;''Manchester Guardian''<ref>{{citation |last=author unknown |title=First arrival in the Port of Manchester of a cargo of goods for bond |newspaper=The Times |page=6 |date=10 October 1844}}\n</ref>|}}\n\nHowever, this venture was less successful than expected, as is evidenced by a letter to ''[[The Observer]]'' later that year, also printed in ''The Times'':\n\n{{quote|<center>MANCHESTER A BONDING PORT</center> After the pressing demands which have been made by some of our principal manufacturing towns for the privileges of inland bonded warehouses for goods subject to Customs duties, it would naturally be supposed that the formation of a Custom-house establishment at Manchester would have occasioned a vast quantity of business in that extensive seat of British manufacturers; but we are informed that the result is very different from what had been expected. Although the system has been introduced into Manchester only as an experiment and a large establishment has been formed entirely of old and experienced officers; under the impression that the extent of business there would require the constant services of well tried men, we believe that, up to the present period, little trade has passed through the Manchester Custom-house and the officers' duties are nearly approaching to a sinecure. The total annual expense of this establishment, exclusive of that for the Custom-house and warehouse is \u00a32,620. The town council of the borough of Manchester, however, are made liable, under the act of the 7th and 8th of Victoria cap 81, to the charges of maintaining this establishment, and the public are thereby exonerated from the expense. <br />-&nbsp;''Observer''<ref>{{citation |last=author unknown |title=Manchester a bonding port |newspaper=The Times |page=2 |date= 3 December 1844}}</ref>|}}\n\nBetween 1849 and 1851 the competition between the Trustees and the railway companies intensified.  Agreements and alliances were made and broken.  Their major opponents were the London and North Western Railway and the [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]] who reduced tariffs and took business away from the canals.  For the first time the railways carried more trade between Liverpool and the towns of central Lancashire than the canals.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=195\u2013225}}</ref>  The value of the traffic carried by the Bridgewater Canal in 1851 was the lowest in the time it was administered by the Trustees.<ref name=mather358/>  In 1851 the Earl of Ellesmere hosted [[Royal visits to Manchester and Salford during the reign of Queen Victoria|a visit to Manchester]] by [[Queen Victoria]] and [[Albert, Prince Consort|Prince Albert]].  They stayed at Worsley Hall, with a view of the canal, and were given a trip between [[Patricroft railway station]] and Worsley Hall, on state barges.  Large crowds had gathered to cheer the royal party, which apparently frightened the horses drawing the barge so much that they fell into the canal.<ref>{{Harvnb|Corbett|1974|p=43}}</ref>\n\nThe Trustees spent much time between 1851 and 1855 in negotiations to ease the competition, especially that from the London and North Western Railway.  The most likely allies seemed to be other railway companies, including the [[Shrewsbury and Birmingham Railway|Shrewsbury and Birmingham]] and the [[Shrewsbury to Chester Line|Shrewsbury and Chester]] railway companies, and the Great Western Railway.  Of these, the most likely seemed to be the Great Western Railway who, in their concern to expand northwards were willing to help the Trustees with the carriage of their traffic to the south.  However years of negotiations came to no agreement and, in the end, the Trustees' railway deal was done with the London and North Western Railway, who agreed to cooperate with the onward passage of the Trustees' traffic.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=226\u2013256}}</ref>\n\nOn 28&nbsp;June 1855 James Loch, the Superintendent, died and was succeeded by [[Algernon Egerton|Hon. Algernon Fulke Egerton]], Lord Ellesmere's third son.  He was then aged 29, and had been educated at [[Harrow School|Harrow]] and [[Christ Church, Oxford]]; he had been destined for a political life and had no experience of managing coal mines or canals.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|p=267}}</ref>  Since James Loch had been appointed, he had been mainly in control of the management of the Trustees, assisted by his son [[George Loch]].  During this time the role of Fereday Smith had been diminished; initially appointed as Deputy Superintendent, his position was reduced to that of Principal Agent in 1845.  With the arrival of the inexperienced Algernon Egerton, Fereday Smith had a much greater say in the management.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=268\u2013269}}</ref>  During the previous four years the Lochs had been reluctant to invest in improvements to the canal or Runcorn Dock, despite the increasing demand for the passage of goods through the dock, and the profits made during these years became stagnant.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=259\u2013267}}</ref>  Fereday Smith had been keen on expansion<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|p=260}}</ref> and now his opportunity came.  He first reduced the top-heavy administration of the Trust,<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=269\u2013270}}</ref> and then took on the planning of the expansion of the business.  The [[Steamboat|steamers]] owned by the Trustees had been neglected and were in a poor state; these were repaired or sold.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=272\u2013273}}</ref>\n\nGeorge Loch, who had been opposed to using the Trustees' investments for improvements to the canals or docks, died in 1857. Between 1857 and 1872 the Trustees provided more capital for improvements from their own resources than at any previous time.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|p=280}}</ref>  The [[Runcorn and Weston Canal]] was built in 1858\u201359, providing a connection between Runcorn Docks and the [[River Weaver|Weaver Navigation]].  A new [[half tide dock]], the [[Port of Runcorn#Runcorn Docks|Alfred Dock]] was opened at Runcorn in 1860.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|p=281}}</ref>  [[Electric telegraph]] was installed in 1861\u201362.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|p=288}}</ref>\n\nIn 1862 the 2nd&nbsp;Earl of Ellesmere died and his son and heir, the [[Francis Egerton, 3rd Earl of Ellesmere|3rd&nbsp;Earl]] was a [[Minor (law)|minor]], aged 15.  This gave Algernon Egerton even more power to invest the profits of the company in developments.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=280\u2013281}}</ref>  Negotiations were made to increase sea-borne trade, both British and foreign, through the canal.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=283\u2013285}}</ref>  Building started on a new dock at Runcorn in 1867. Work was carried out in the Mersey estuary around the docks to improve access for vessels.  Some of this was carried out in conjunction with the London and North Western Railway who were building a [[Runcorn Railway Bridge|bridge]] across Runcorn Gap to take their line from Weaver Junction to Liverpool; the railway paid half the cost of the improvements, amounting to about \u00a320,000 (\u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|20000|1867|r=-4}}|0}} today).{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=285\u2013286}}</ref>  Improvements were made to the Trustees' facilities at Liverpool, to the Mersey and Irwell Navigation and to the Bridgewater Canal itself.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=287\u2013291}}</ref>  Agreements were made with the railway companies to cooperate on the transit of goods and the rates of carriage<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=292\u2013304}}</ref> and \"the Trustees' fortunes entered a calmer phase\".<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|p=299}}</ref>\n\n== Subsequent owners ==\n[[File:Barton Swing Aqueduct.jpg|thumb|right|Barton Swing Aqueduct, built to replace the original aqueduct during construction of the [[Manchester Ship Canal]]]]\nIn 1872 the Bridgewater Navigation Company Ltd was formed, and on Monday 9 September the canal was purchased in the names of [[Edward Watkin|Sir Edward William Watkin]] and William Philip Price, respectively chairmen of the [[Manchester, Sheffield and Lincolnshire Railway]] and the [[Midland Railway]] for \u00a31,120,000.<ref>{{citation |title=The Times newspaper: The Bridgewater Canal | url=http://archive.timesonline.co.uk/tol/viewArticle.arc?toDate=1985-12-31&fromDate=1785-01-01&currentPageNumber=1&resultsPerPage=10&sortBy=default&offset=0&viewName=&addFilters=&removeFilters=&addCat=&queryKeywords=bridgewater+canal&sectionId=1040&currPgSmartSet=1&pageId=ARCHIVE-The_Times-1872-09-09-10&articleId=ARCHIVE-The_Times-1872-09-09-10-003&xmlpath=&pubId=17&totalResults=1638&addRefineFilters=&removeRefineFilters=&addRefineCat=&next_Page=false&prev_Page=false&date_dd_From=1&date_mm_From=01&date_yyyy_From=1785&date_dd_to_range=31&date_mm_to_range=12&date_yyyy_to_range=1985&date_dd_from_precise=1&date_mm_from_precise=01&date_yyyy_from_precise=1785&isDateSearch=false&dateSearchType=range&refineQuerykeywordText= |date=9 September 1872|accessdate=19 July 2008 |location=London |first1=Rachel |last1=Sylvester |first2=Sam |last2=Coates}}</ref>{{sfn|Mather|1970|pp=334\u2013335|ps=}}  The canal was sold again in 1885, when the [[Manchester Ship Canal]] Company paid the Bridgewater Navigation Company \u00a31,710,000 for all their property.<ref>{{citation |title=Bridgewater Canal History, 1872 - Change and Consolidation |url=http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/timeline9.html |publisher=The Manchester Ship Canal Company |accessdate=2 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121225344/http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/timeline9.html |archivedate=21 November 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>  The construction of the ship canal forced the removal of Barton Aqueduct and the construction of [[Barton Swing Aqueduct]], as the former was too low for the vessels which would use the new canal.  In 1907 The Manchester Ship Canal (Bridgewater Canal) Act 1907 was passed, permitting coal mining near the canal between Monton Bridge and Leigh, in exchange for which the mine owners were obliged to pay the associated costs of keeping the canal open and navigable.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Manchester Ship Canal (Bridgewater Canal) Act 1907 (Amendment) Order 1996 |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/1996/1484/note/made |publisher=The National Archives |accessdate=23 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1923 Bridgewater Estates Ltd was formed to acquire the [[Earl of Ellesmere|Ellesmere family]] estate in Worsley. In 1984 Bridgewater Estates Ltd was purchased by a subsidiary of [[Peel Group|Peel Holdings]]. In 1987 Highams acquired a majority shareholding of the Manchester Ship Canal Company (subsequently the shares held by Highams were transferred to Peel Holdings).  In 1994 the Manchester Ship Canal Company became a wholly owned subsidiary of the Peel Holdings group. In 2004 ownership of the Manchester Ship Canal Company was transferred to the Peel Ports group.<ref>{{citation |title=Bridgewater Canal History, 1920s to present day |url=http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/timeline11.html |publisher=The Manchester Ship Canal Company |accessdate=2 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121221130/http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/timeline11.html |archivedate=21 November 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Current status ==\n[[File:Barton-upon-Irwell 11.05.02R.jpg|thumb|right|Aerial view of Barton-on-Irwell in 2002 looking SE showing the [[Barton Swing Aqueduct]] over the ship canal (left) and the [[Barton Road Swing Bridge]] (right)]]\n\nThe Bridgewater is often wrongly argued to be the first true canal in England, as it relied upon existing watercourses as sources of water rather than as navigable routes.<ref>{{Citation|title=In Brief|url=http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/history.html|publisher=The Manchester Ship Canal Company|accessdate=5 December 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705023435/http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/history.html|archivedate=5 July 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>The [[Sankey Canal|Sankey Brook Navigation]] also has a claim to be the first modern British canal.</ref>  It now terminates in Runcorn basin, just before the disused flight of 10 locks<ref name=Runcornlockssociety>{{Citation|title=Runcorn Locks Restoration Society |url=http://www.runcornlocks.org.uk/ |accessdate=14 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705104636/http://www.runcornlocks.org.uk/ |archivedate=5 July 2008 }}</ref> which (before the approach road to the [[Silver Jubilee Bridge]] was built) used to lower the canal to the Runcorn Docks on the River Mersey and later, to the Manchester Ship Canal. The old line of locks in Runcorn fell into disuse in the late 1930s, and they were closed under the Ship Canal Act of 1949 and filled in. The Ship Canal Act of 1966 allowed the closure and filling in of the newer line of locks.<ref>{{Harvnb|Starkey|1983|p=206}}</ref>  The gates from this flight of locks were removed and installed at Devizes on the [[Kennet and Avon Canal]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}  The Duke's warehouse in Manchester was demolished in 1960.<ref name=pb15/>\n\nThe canal has suffered three breaches; one soon after opening, another in 1971 near the [[River Bollin]] aqueduct,<ref name=BollinLeak>{{Citation |title=Maintaining an Ageing Network |publisher=Manchester Ship Canal Company |url=http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/timeline12.html |accessdate=2 July 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121221942/http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/timeline12.html |archivedate=21 November 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and another in the summer of 2005 when a sluice gate failed in Manchester.<ref name=SluiceFailure>{{Citation | title=Bridgewater Canal News&nbsp;\u2014 Sluice Failure Drains Canal | url=http://www.penninewaterways.co.uk/news19.htm | publisher = Pennine Waterways | accessdate = 18 September 2008 | format= \u2013 <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=intitle%3ABridgewater+Canal+News%26nbsp%3B%E2%80%94+Sluice+Failure+Drains+Canal&as_publication=&as_ylo=&as_yhi=&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup>|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070622083851/http://www.penninewaterways.co.uk/news19.htm |archivedate = 22 June 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Crane (machine)|Cranes]] are located at intervals along the canal's length to allow boards to be dropped into slots in the banks.  These allow sections of the canal to be isolated in the event of a leak.\n\nThe canal now forms an integral part of the [[Cheshire Ring]] network of canals.<ref>{{Citation | title = Information about Bridgewater Canal | url = http://www.waterscape.com/canals-and-rivers/bridgewater-canal | publisher = British Waterways | accessdate = 5 December 2008 }}</ref>  Pleasure craft have been allowed on the canal since 1952.<ref name=Penninewaterways/>\n\nThe new road crossing of the Mersey now under construction may allow a realignment of the bridge approach road and the complete restoration of the original flight of locks<ref>{{Citation|title=Bridgewater Canal&nbsp;\u2013 Runcorn Locks (Under Restoration)|url=http://www.waterways.org.uk/Waterways/PrincipalNavigations/BridgewaterCanalRuncornLocksUnderRestoration|publisher=The Inland Waterways Association, 2006|accessdate=14 August 2008|format= \u2013 <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=intitle%3ABridgewater+Canal%26nbsp%3B%E2%80%93+Runcorn+Locks+%28Under+Restoration%29&as_publication=&as_ylo=&as_yhi=&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup>|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071109223556/http://www.waterways.org.uk/Waterways/PrincipalNavigations/BridgewaterCanalRuncornLocksUnderRestoration |archivedate = 9 November 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 thus re-opening the link to Runcorn Docks, the Runcorn and Weston Canal, the River Mersey, the Manchester Ship Canal, and the River Weaver.  This would create a new ring route for leisure boats involving the Trent and Mersey Canal, the [[Anderton Boat Lift]] and the River Weaver.<ref name=Runcornlockssociety/>\n\nThe [[Hulme Locks Branch Canal]] in Manchester is now disused, and on 26 May 1995 was replaced by the nearby Pomona Lock.\n\n=== Bridgewater Way ===\nThe Bridgewater Way is a scheme to redevelop the canal and make it more accessible to users, particularly cyclists. The {{convert|40|mi|adj=on}} development, which includes a new towpath, will form part of the National Cycle and Footpath Network as Regional Route number 82.<ref name=Bridgewaterway>{{Citation | title = Bridgewater Brochure 2008 | url = http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/bridgewaterbrochure.pdf | format = PDF | publisher = The Bridgewater Canal Trust | accessdate = 8 August 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081121223905/http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/bridgewaterbrochure.pdf | archivedate = 21 November 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|United Kingdom|Transport|Cheshire}}\n* [[Canals of the United Kingdom]]\n* [[History of the British canal system]]\n\n== References ==\n===Notes===\n{{notelist|notes=}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{citation |title=Reader's Digest Library of Modern Knowledge |publisher=[[Reader's Digest]] |year=1978}}\n* {{citation |title=The Bridgewater Canal Handbook |publisher=Ed. J. Burrow & Co. |year= |isbn=}}\n:Although no details of author and date are given, this is likely to be a reliable source as it was published for the [[Manchester Ship Canal]] Company in 1973 or later (a picture of the reopening of the canal is on the cover).\n* {{citation |last=Aspin |first=Chris |title=The First industrial Society: Lancashire 1750\u20131850 |year=1995 |publisher=Carnegie Publishing |isbn=1-85936-016-5}}\n* {{citation |last=Chaloner |first=William Henry |title=People and Industries |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xq7BFVtwANcC |year=1963 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=0-7146-1284-7}}\n* {{citation |last=Collins |first=Arthur |title=Collins's peerage of England; genealogical, biographical, and historical |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r_M6AAAAIAAJ |publisher=F. C. and J. Rivington, Otridge and Son |year=1812}}\n* {{citation |last=Corbett |first=John |title=Pleasant Reminiscences of the Nineteenth Century and Suggestions for Improvements in the Twentieth. |publisher=E. J. Morton |year=1974 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b0KEHwAACAAJ |isbn=0-85972-006-3}}\n*{{citation |last=Hayes |first=Geoffrey |title=Collieries and their Railways in the Manchester Coalfields |publisher=Landmark |year=2004 |isbn=1-84306-135-X}}\n* {{citation |last=Kindleberger |first=Charles Poor |title=A Financial History of Western Europe |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PFgIE7_eYwwC |publisher=Oxford University Press US |year=1993 |isbn=0-19-507738-5}}\n* {{citation |last=Mather |first=F. A. |title=After the Canal Duke |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1970 |isbn=}}\n* {{citation |last=Mullineux |first=Frank |date=1959 |title=The Duke of Bridgewater's Canal |publisher=Eccles and District History Society.}}\n* {{citation |last=Nickson |first=Charles |title=History of Runcorn  |publisher=Mackie & Co. |year=1887}}\n* {{citation |last=Parkinson-Bailey |first=John |title=Manchester: An Architectural History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ush5WC9BM_gC |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=0-7190-5606-3 |year=2000}}\n* {{citation |last=Pickering |first=Danby |title=The Statutes at Large: From the Magna Charta, to the End of the Eleventh Parliament of Great Britain, Anno 1761 {continued to 1807} |publisher=J Bentham |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GqwuAAAAIAAJ |year=1807}}\n* {{citation |last=Priestley |first=Joseph |title=Historical Account of the Navigable Rivers, Canals, and Railways of Great Britain |publisher=Longman, Green |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eUqIucVmZjwC |year=1831}}\n* {{citation |last=Skempton |first=Sir Alec |title=A Biographical Dictionary of Civil Engineers in Great Britain and Ireland: 1500 to 1830 |publisher=Thomas Telford |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jeOMfpYMOtYC |year=2002 |isbn=0-7277-2939-X}}\n* {{citation |last=Smiles |first=Samuel | title= Lives of the Engineers |publisher=Read Books |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PdmctboVgsYC |year=2006 |isbn=1-4067-9868-1}}\n* {{citation |last=Starkey |first=H. F. |title =Schooner Port: Two Centuries of Upper Mersey Sail  |publisher=G. W. & A. Hesketh  |year=1983 |isbn=0-905777-34-4}}\n* {{citation |last=Starkey |first=H. F. |title=Old Runcorn |publisher=Halton Borough Council |year=1990 |isbn=}}\n* {{citation |last=Sweeney |first=D. J. |title=A Lancashire Triangle Part Two |publisher=Triangle Publishing |year=1997 |isbn=0-9529333-2-2}}\n* {{citation |last=Timbs |first=John |title=Stories of Inventors and Discoverers in Science and the Useful Arts: A Book for Old and Young |year=1860 |publisher=Harper & Brothers}}\n* {{citation|last=Tomlinson |first=Victor I. |title=The Manchester Bolton And Bury Canal |publisher=The Manchester Bolton & Bury Canal Society |url=http://www.mbbcs.org.uk/society/sales.htm |year=1991 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081010144006/http://www.mbbcs.org.uk/society/sales.htm |archivedate=2008-10-10 }}\n* {{citation |last=Ware |first=Michael E. |title=Britain's lost waterways |year=1989 |publisher=Moorland |isbn=0-86190-327-7}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=Y7c2rVtmyPcC James Brindley: An Illustrated Life of James Brindley, 1716\u20131772]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category-inline|Bridgewater Canal}}\n* [http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/ Bridgewater Canal website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071117233235/http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/location2.html Bridgewater Canal map]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040805130654/http://www.penninewaterways.co.uk/bridgewater/index.htm Website with description and photographs]\n* [http://www.isd.salford.ac.uk/library/resources/special/duke-bridgewater.xml Duke of Bridgewater Archive from the University of Salford site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060924230857/http://www.d.lane.btinternet.co.uk/canal.html Duke of Bridgewater's Underground Canal at Worsley]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070403183315/http://www.agcm.org.uk/museum.shtml Astley Green Colliery Museum]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071116063128/http://www.shipcanal.co.uk/ Manchester Ship Canal Company website]\n\n<!--spacing-->\n\n{{Canals of Britain}}\n\n[[Category:Canals in England]]\n[[Category:Canals in Trafford]]\n[[Category:Canals in Warrington]]\n[[Category:Canals in the Metropolitan Borough of Wigan]]\n[[Category:Industrial Revolution]]\n[[Category:Canals in Cheshire]]\n[[Category:Irwell Valley]]\n[[Category:Canals opened in 1761]]\n[[Category:1761 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the canal in North West England|the canal in Somerset|Bridgwater and Taunton Canal}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox Canal\n  |name                    = Bridgewater Canal\n  |image                   = Worsley packet house closeup large image.jpg\n  |image_size              = 325px\n  |image_caption           = The Packet House at Worsley, on the canal\n  |former_names            = \n  |original_owner          = \n  |engineer                = [[John Gilbert (agent)|John Gilbert]], [[James Brindley]]\n  |other_engineer          = \n  |date_act                = 1759, 1760, 1762, 1766, 1795\n  |date_began              = \n  |date_use                = 1761\n  |date_completed          = 1761\n  |date_extended           = 1762\n  |date_closed             = \n  |date_restored           = \n  |len_ft                     = 72\n  |len_in                  = 0\n  |original_boat_length_ft    = \n  |original_boat_length_in = \n  |len_note                = \n  |beam_ft                    = 14\n  |beam_in                 = 9\n  |original_beam_ft           = \n  |original_beam_in        = \n  |beam_note               = \n  |start_point             = [[Worsley]]\n  |original_start          = \n  |start_note              = \n  |end_point               = [[Runcorn]]\n  |original_end            = [[Manchester]]\n  |end_note                = ''See article''\n  |branch                  = \n  |branch_of               = \n  |connects_to             = [[Rochdale Canal]], [[Trent and Mersey Canal]], [[Leeds and Liverpool Canal]], [[Manchester Ship Canal]]\n  |length_mi                  = 41\n  |locks                   = 0\n  |original_num_locks      = 10 at Runcorn\n  |lock_note               = ''See article''\n  |status                  = Open\n  |navigation_authority    = Manchester Ship Canal Company\n}}\n{{Bridgewater Canal map}}\nThe '''Bridgewater Canal''' connects [[Runcorn]], [[Manchester]] and [[Leigh, Greater Manchester|Leigh]], in [[North West England]]. It was commissioned by [[Francis Egerton, 3rd Duke of Bridgewater]], to transport coal from his mines in [[Worsley]] to Manchester. It was opened in 1761 from Worsley to Manchester, and later extended from Manchester to Runcorn, and then from Worsley to Leigh.\n\nThe [[canal]] is connected to the [[Manchester Ship Canal]] via a lock at Cornbrook; to the [[Rochdale Canal]] in Manchester; to the [[Trent and Mersey Canal]] at [[Preston Brook]], southeast of Runcorn; and to the [[Leeds and Liverpool Canal]] at Leigh. It once connected with the [[River Mersey]] at Runcorn but has since been cut off by a slip road to the [[Silver Jubilee Bridge]].\n\nFollowing the construction of the [[Sankey Brook Navigation]], Bridgewater has been argued to be the first true canal of the [[Industrial Revolution]] in England, and it required the construction of an [[navigable aqueduct|aqueduct]] to cross the [[River Irwell]], one of the first of its kind. Its success helped inspire a period of intense canal building in Britain, known as [[Canal Mania]]. It later faced intense competition from the [[Liverpool and Manchester Railway]] and the [[Macclesfield Canal]]. Navigable throughout its history, it is one of the few canals in Britain not to have been nationalised, and remains privately owned. Pleasure craft now use the canal which forms part of the [[Cheshire Ring]] network of canals.\n\n== Design and construction ==\n[[Francis Egerton, 3rd Duke of Bridgewater]], owned some of the coal mines dug to supply [[North West England]] with fuel for the [[steam engine]]s instrumental in powering England's [[Industrial Revolution]].<ref name=pb15>{{Harvnb|Parkinson-Bailey|2000|p=15}}</ref><ref name=chal34>{{Harvnb|Chaloner|1963|p=34}}</ref>  The duke transported his coal along the [[Mersey and Irwell Navigation]] and also by [[packhorse]], but each method was inefficient and expensive; river transport was subject to the vagaries of river navigation,<ref>Vessels were affected by tide levels, and the shared use of water by industry</ref> and the amount of coal packhorses could carry was limited by its relative weight.{{sfn|Kindleberger|1993|p=192|ps=}}  The duke's underground mines also suffered from persistent flooding, caused by the [[geology]] of the Middle [[Coal Measures]], where the [[Worsley Four Foot mine|coal seam]] lies beneath a layer of permeable [[sandstone]].\n\nHaving visited the [[Canal du Midi]] in France and watched the construction of the [[Sankey Canal]] in England,<ref name=Penninewaterways>{{cite web |title=History of the Bridgewater Canal |url=http://www.penninewaterways.co.uk/bridgewater/bri2.htm |publisher=Pennine Waterways |accessdate=14 August 2008}}</ref> the duke's solution to these problems was to build an underground canal at Worsley, connected to a surface canal between [[Worsley]] and [[Salford, Greater Manchester|Salford]].<ref name=\"Priestleyp89\">{{Harvnb|Priestley|1831|p=89}}</ref>  In addition to easing overland transport difficulties and providing drainage for his mines, an underground canal would provide a reliable source of water for the surface canal, and also eliminate the need to lift the coal to the surface (an expensive and difficult proposition). The canal boats would carry {{convert|30|LT}} at a time, pulled by only one horse&nbsp;\u2013 more than ten times the amount of cargo per horse that was possible with a cart.{{sfn|N/A|1978|p=990|ps=}}  The duke and his estate manager [[John Gilbert (agent)|John Gilbert]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Coal and Water&nbsp;\u2014 The Bridgewater Canal, John Gilbert |url=http://www.peak41.co.uk/coalandwater/johngilbert.html |publisher=Mike Higginbottom |accessdate=14 August 2008|format= \u2013 <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=intitle%3ACoal+and+Water%26nbsp%3B%E2%80%94+The+Bridgewater+Canal%2C+John+Gilbert&as_publication=&as_ylo=&as_yhi=&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup> |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070718221904/http://www.peak41.co.uk/coalandwater/johngilbert.html |archivedate=18 July 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref> produced a plan of the canal, and in 1759 obtained an [[Acts of Parliament in the United Kingdom|Act of Parliament]], enabling its construction.<ref name=\"Priestleyp89\"/><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/a2a/records.aspx?cat=129-bw |title=Bridgewater Estates Collection |publisher=The National Archives |accessdate=23 June 2013}}</ref>{{efn|An Act to enable the most noble Francis Duke of Bridgewater, to make a navigable cut or canal from a certain place in the township of Salford, to or near Worsley Mill, and Middlewood, in the manor of Worsley, and to or near a place called Hollin Ferry, in the county palatine of Lancaster. 32nd George II.}}\n\n[[James Brindley]] was brought in for his technical expertise (having previously installed a pumping system at the nearby [[Wet Earth Colliery]]), and after a six-day visit suggested varying the route of the proposed canal away from Salford, instead taking it across the [[River Irwell]] to [[Stretford]] and thereon into Manchester.<ref name=\"Skemptonp76\">{{Harvnb|Skempton|2002|p=76}}</ref>  This route would make connecting to any future canals much easier, and would also increase competition with the Mersey and Irwell Navigation company.<ref name=\"Ref-1\">Boughey, Joseph. (1998) Hadfield's British Canals, Sutton Publishing, {{ISBN|0-7509-1840-3}}</ref>{{sfn|Mather|1970|p=xvi|ps=}}  Brindley moved into [[Worsley Old Hall]] and spent 46&nbsp;days surveying the proposed route, which to cross the Irwell would require the construction of an aqueduct at [[Barton-upon-Irwell]].<ref name=chal34/>  At the duke's behest, in January 1760 Brindley also travelled to London to give evidence before a [[parliamentary committee]].  The duke therefore gained a second Act of Parliament, which superseded the original.<ref name=\"Priestleyp89\"/><ref name=\"Skemptonp76\"/>{{efn|An Act to enable the most noble Francis Duke of Bridgewater, to make a navigable cut or canal from a certain place in the township of Salford, over the Irwell, to the town of Manchester, in the county palatine of Lancaster, and to or near Longford Bridge, in the township of Stretford, in the said county.}}\n\nBrindley's planned route began at Worsley and passed southeast through [[Eccles, Greater Manchester|Eccles]], before turning south to cross the River Irwell on the [[Barton Aqueduct]]. From there it continued southeast along the edge of [[Trafford Park]], and then east into Manchester. Although a connection with the Mersey and Irwell Navigation was included in the new Act, at Hulme Locks in [[Castlefield]] (on land previously occupied by [[Hulme Hall, Hulme|Hulme Hall]]), this was not completed until 1838. The terminus would be at Castlefield Basin, where the nearby [[River Medlock]] was to help supply the canal with water.<ref>{{cite web |title=Salford Hundred, Ancestry, Annals and History |url=http://www.mancuniensis.info/WorsleyFPX.htm |publisher=Elaine and Roger Hart, Bolton, Greater Manchester |accessdate=14 August 2008}}</ref>  Boats would unload their cargoes inside the duke's purpose-built warehouse.  There were no locks in Brindley's design, demonstrating{{clarify|whose opinion?|date=January 2011}} his ability as a competent engineer.<ref name=\"Skemptonp76\"/>  The Barton Aqueduct was built relatively quickly for the time; work commenced in September 1760 and the first boat crossed on 17&nbsp;July 1761.{{sfn|Collins|1812|p=213|ps=}}\n\n[[File:BrownManchesterMuralBridgewater.jpg|right|thumb|''The Opening of the Bridgewater Canal A.D. 1761'' by [[Ford Madox Brown]], one of ''[[The Manchester Murals]]'' at [[Manchester Town Hall]]]]\n[[File:Bridgewater Canal at Barton 1891.jpg|right|thumb|Brindley's aqueduct, replaced late in the 19th century]]\nThe duke invested a large sum of money in the scheme. From Worsley to Manchester its construction cost \u00a3168,000 (equivalent to \u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|168000|1761|r=-1}}}} in {{Inflation-year|UK}}),{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}{{sfn|Timbs|1860|p=363|ps=}} but its advantages over land and river transport meant that within a year of its opening in 1761, the price of coal in Manchester fell by about half.<ref name=Bridgewatercollieries>{{citation |title=The Times newspaper: Bridgewater Collieries |url=http://archive.timesonline.co.uk/tol/viewArticle.arc?toDate=1985-12-31&fromDate=1785-01-01&currentPageNumber=1&resultsPerPage=10&sortBy=default&offset=0&viewName=&addFilters=&removeFilters=&addCat=&queryKeywords=bridgewater+canal&sectionId=1040&currPgSmartSet=1&pageId=ARCHIVE-The_Times-1913-12-01-08&articleId=ARCHIVE-The_Times-1913-12-01-08-001&xmlpath=&pubId=17&totalResults=1638&addRefineFilters=&removeRefineFilters=&addRefineCat=&next_Page=false&prev_Page=false&date_dd_From=1&date_mm_From=01&date_yyyy_From=1785&date_dd_to_range=31&date_mm_to_range=12&date_yyyy_to_range=1985&date_dd_from_precise=1&date_mm_from_precise=01&date_yyyy_from_precise=1785&isDateSearch=false&dateSearchType=range&refineQuerykeywordText= |date=1 December 1913 |accessdate=19 July 2008 |location=London |first1=Rachel |last1=Sylvester |first2=Sam |last2=Coates}}</ref>  This success helped inspire a period of intense canal building, known as [[Canal Mania]].{{sfn|Kindleberger|1993|pp=192\u2013193|ps=}} Along with its stone aqueduct at Barton-upon-Irwell, the Bridgewater Canal was considered a major engineering achievement. One commentator wrote that when finished, \"[the canal] will be the most extraordinary thing in the Kingdom, if not in Europe. The boats in some places are to go underground, and in other places over a navigable river, without communicating with its waters\".<ref name=\"Ref-1\"/>\n\nIn addition to the duke's warehouse at Manchester, more buildings were built by Brindley and extended to Alport Street (now called [[Deansgate]]).<ref name=pb15/>  The warehouses were of timber-frame design, with load-bearing hand-made brick walls, supported on cast iron posts. The duke's warehouse was badly damaged by fire in 1789 but was rebuilt.<ref name=pb15/><ref name=pb17>{{Harvnb|Parkinson-Bailey|2000|p=17}}</ref>\n[[File:Bridgewater foundary.gif|thumb|right|Bridgewater Foundry at Patricroft, 1839]]\n\n=== Manchester to Runcorn extension ===\nIn September 1761, with his assistant Hugh Oldham,{{sfn|Skempton|2002|p=79|ps=}} Brindley surveyed an extension from Longford Bridge to Hempstones, near [[Halton, Cheshire]].<ref name=\"Skemptonp76\"/>  He assisted in obtaining Parliamentary approval for the Bridgewater Canal Extension Act of 1762<ref>An Act to enable the most noble Francis Duke of Bridgewater, to make a navigable cut or canal from Longford Bridge, in the township of Stretford, in the county palatine of Lancaster, to the River Mersey, at a place called the Hempstones, in the township of Halton, in the county of Chester.</ref> which allowed the construction of an extension to the canal, from Manchester, to the River Mersey at [[Runcorn]].<ref name=chal35>{{Harvnb|Chaloner|1963|p=35}}</ref>  Despite objections from the Mersey and Irwell Navigation Company,<ref name=\"Skemptonp76\"/> [[Royal assent]] was given on 24&nbsp;March 1762.<ref name=anon29>{{Harvnb|Anon|p=29}}</ref>  A junction, Waters Meeting, was created in [[Trafford Park]], at which the new extension branched south through [[Stretford]], [[Sale, Greater Manchester|Sale]], [[Altrincham]], [[Lymm]] and finally to [[Runcorn]].\n\nIn December 1761 Brindley undertook a survey of the route at Runcorn. His initial plan was to make the terminus at Hempstones, east of Runcorn Gap,<!-- where the Mersey narrows between the town of Runcorn and a promontory which was to later form part of the town of [[Widnes]] - not certain this is relevant so will leave hidden for now--> but following a study of the tides and depth of water there, he decided instead to build the terminus west of Runcorn Gap.{{sfn|Starkey|1990|p=125|ps=}}  This change was designed to accommodate [[Mersey Flat|Mersey flats]], although the low fixed bridges required that traffic on the canal be able to lower or unship their masts.<ref name=st13>{{Harvnb|Starkey|1983|p=13}}</ref>  Runcorn basin was almost {{convert|90|ft|m|0}} above the Mersey,{{sfn|Nickson|1887|p=159|ps=}} so a flight of ten locks, described as \"the wonder of their time\",{{sfn|Starkey|1990|p=127|ps=}} was built to connect the two.  Nine locks had a fall of {{convert|2|m|ft|0}}, with a fall at the river lock of more than {{convert|6|m|ft|0}} at low water. It allowed vessels to enter and leave the canal on any [[tide]]. The connection to the Mersey was made on 1&nbsp;January 1773.<ref name=st126/>  The river's tidal action tended to deposit [[silt]] around the lower entrance to the locks, so to counteract this a channel, equipped with gates at each end and known as the Duke's Gut, was cut through the marshes upriver from the locks.  At high tide the gates were closed, and with the ebb of the tide were opened to release water, which scoured the silt from the entrance to the locks.  The cut created an island, known as Runcorn Island, crossed by Castle Bridge.{{sfn|1970|p=20}}{{sfn|Starkey|1990|pp=128\u2013129|ps=}}<ref>It was known as Castle Bridge because it made a connection with a rocky promontory which had once been the site of a castle built by [[Ethelfleda]] to defend her kingdom of [[Mercia]] from [[Viking]] invasion.</ref>\n\n[[File:Stretford.jpg|thumb|left|Ordnance Survey map of 1843 showing the canal crossing the River Mersey at Barfoot Bridge, Stretford]]\n[[File:Runcorn soapworks.jpg|left|thumb|The canal at Runcorn between the factories]]\n[[File:OS One-inch Sheet 100 Extract Runcorn Bridgewater Canal 1966.jpg|left|thumb|Extract from OS one-inch sheet 100 showing the junction between the Bridgewater Canal and the Manchester Ship Canal at Runcorn, with the flight of locks, as it was in 1966]]\nThe connection to Manchester was delayed by [[Brooke baronets|Sir Richard Brooke]] of [[Norton Priory]]. Concerned that boatmen might poach his game and wildfowl, Brooke did not want the canal to pass through his land. The Act included several stipulations: the canal should not come within {{convert|325|m|ft|0}} of his house; the towpath should be on the south side of the canal, furthest away from Brooke's house; there should be no quays, buildings, hedges or fences to obstruct the view; no vessels were to be moored within {{convert|1000|m|ft|0}} of the house, other than during construction.  Eventually, though, a compromise was reached.  This included the construction of a link to the [[Trent and Mersey Canal]] at [[Preston Brook]] (permitted by the Trent and Mersey Canal Act of 1766),{{sfn|Priestley|1831|p=90|ps=}} and the building of the canal's terminus to the west of Runcorn Gap.<ref name=st126/>  The Trent and Mersey link gave the Duke access to the Midlands, and forestalled the Weaver Trustees from making their own junction with the canal.{{sfn|Mather|1970|pp=xvi\u2013xvii|ps=}} The new extension also met with opposition from the Mersey and Irwell Navigation, until the duke purchased a controlling interest in the company.<ref name=chal35/>  The first part of the new extension was opened in 1767,<ref name=\"Chalonerp36\">{{Harvnb|Chaloner|1963|p=36}}</ref> and completed in full by March 1776,<ref name=st126>{{Harvnb|Starkey|1990|p=126}}</ref> but Brindley did not live to see its completion; it was continued by his brother-in-law, [[Hugh Henshall]].<ref name=anon29/>\n\nThe total cost of the canal, from Worsley to Manchester and from Longford Bridge to the Mersey at Runcorn, was \u00a3220,000.{{sfn|Nickson|1887|p=161|ps=}}  Alongside the Mersey, the duke built [[Port of Runcorn|Runcorn Dock]], several warehouses, and [[Bridgewater House, Runcorn|Bridgewater House]], a temporary home from which he could supervise operations at the Runcorn end.  Two locks up from the tideway was a small [[dry dock]].<ref name=st13/>\n\n=== Sale to Stockport branch ===\nIn 1766 the Duke gained a fourth act of parliament for a branch canal between [[Sale, Greater Manchester|Sale Moor]] and [[Stockport]] which was to follow the valley of the Mersey.  The Act was applied for to counter a proposed canal that would give the towns of [[Stockport]] and [[Macclesfield]] access to the Mersey, via the [[River Weaver]].<ref name=\"Chalonerp36\"/>  The work was not done, the Act lapsed and this section of canal was never built.<ref>{{citation|title=1765 - From Sale to Stockport|url=http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/timeline5.html|publisher=The Manchester Ship Canal Company|accessdate=14 August 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121224755/http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/timeline5.html|archivedate=21 November 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOver two decades later, the nearby [[Manchester Bolton & Bury Canal]] had sought a connection to other waterways, and it appears that the Duke had planned to limit the activities of the new company.  On 15 December 1792 the Duke purchased a portion of the [[Ringspiggot]] estate in Salford which blocked the MB&BC's plans to build a riverside basin and wharfs there.<ref name=\"Tomlinsonp33\">{{Harvnb|Tomlinson|1991|p=33}}</ref>\n\n=== Worsley to Leigh extension ===\nIn 1795 the duke secured a fifth Act which enabled him to extend the canal a further {{convert|5|mi|km|0}} from Worsley via [[Boothstown]], [[Astley, Greater Manchester|Astley Green]] and [[Bedford, Greater Manchester|Bedford]] to Leigh.<ref>{{cite web |title=1795 \u2013 From Worsley to Leigh |url=http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/timeline6.html |publisher=The Manchester Ship Canal Company |accessdate=14 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121225106/http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/timeline6.html |archivedate=21 November 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=chal37>{{Harvnb|Chaloner|1963|p=37}}</ref>  The new extension enabled the supply to Manchester of coal from Leigh and the surrounding districts.{{sfn|Smiles|2006|p=272|ps=}}  On 21 June 1819 an Act of Parliament was enacted to create a link between this extension and the [[Leeds and Liverpool Canal]] at [[Wigan]].{{sfn|Tomlinson|1991|p=44|ps=}}\n\nAccess to the canal brought about a rapid development in coal mining on the [[Manchester Coalfield]] west of Worsley. Chaddock pits in the east of Tyldesley were connected to an underground level from Worsley. In 1820, to ease congestion at the Delph in Worsley, Chaddock Pit was connected to the canal at Boothstown basin by an underground canal, the Chaddock Level which ran in a north west direction from the canal at Boothstown to the pit.{{sfn|Hayes|2004|pp=31\u201332|ps=}} Sometime after 1840 Samuel Jackson built a narrow gauge tramroad worked by horses from his [[Astley and Tyldesley Collieries|Gin Pit Colliery]] to Marsland Green where he installed cranes and tipplers to load barges at a wharf. The tramroad was later worked by locomotives.{{sfn|Hayes|2004|p=148|ps=}} In 1867 the [[Fletcher, Burrows and Company|Fletchers]] built a private railway line and the Bedford Basin with facilities for loading coal from [[Howe Bridge]] onto barges. [[Astley Green Colliery]] began winding coal on the north bank of the canal in 1912. In the 1940s and '50s coal was sent to [[Barton Power Station]] and Runcorn Gas Works.{{sfn|Sweeney|1997|p=332|ps=}}\n\n=== Connection to Rochdale Canal ===\n[[File:Map of Manchester 1801.PNG|thumb|right|A map from 1801 showing the Bridgewater and Rochdale canals yet to be connected]]\n[[File:Packet House Worsley.jpg|right|thumb|The Packet House at Worsley, in 1866]]\n[[File:Bridgewater letter 1837.jpg|thumb|right|portrait|Letter to the Bridgewater Canal offices concerning wives sleeping on boats, dated 11&nbsp;November 1837]]\nUpon completion of the [[Rochdale Canal]] in 1804, the two canals were joined at Castlefield.<ref name=pb17/>{{sfn|Pickering|1807|p=663|ps=}}  This connection may have been a factor in the failure of the Manchester Bolton & Bury Canal Company's rival scheme to build a canal between [[Bury, Greater Manchester|Bury]] and Sladen.{{sfn|Tomlinson|1991|pp=34\u201335|ps=}}  The River Medlock, a major source of water for the canal and which was almost as badly polluted as the nearby Irwell, was diverted through a tunnel under the canal at Castlefield by [[Charles Edward Cawley]], a civil engineer for the [[County Borough of Salford|Salford Corporation]] and later [[Member of Parliament#United Kingdom|MP]] for Salford.  The canal was from that point supplied by the much purer water of the Rochdale Canal.{{sfn|Corbett|1974|p=41|ps=}}\n\n=== Mines ===\n{{Main|Worsley Navigable Levels}}\nWorsley Delph, in Worsley, originally a centuries-old [[sandstone]] [[quarry]] near Worsley Brook, was the entrance to the Navigable Levels. It is now a [[Scheduled Monument]].<ref>{{Cite PastScape |num=44278 |desc=Worsley Delph |access-date=30 December 2007 |mode=cs2}}</ref>  Two entrances, built years apart, allow access to the specially built M-boats (also known as [[Starvationers]]), the largest of which could carry {{convert|12|LT}} of coal. Inside the mines {{convert|46|mi|km|0}} of underground canal on four levels, linked by inclined planes, were constructed. The mines ceased production in 1887.<ref name=BLW11>Ware (1989), p.&nbsp;11.</ref>  As the canal passes through Worsley, [[iron oxide]] from the mines has, for many years, stained the water bright orange. The removal of this colouration is currently the subject of a \u00a32.5&nbsp;million remedial scheme.<ref>{{cite web |title=Transformation of Worsley's Orange Canal |url=http://www.coal.gov.uk/media//94807/Page%208%20and%209%20Enviro%20Issue%2013.pdf |format=pdf |accessdate=15 July 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327152417/http://www.coal.gov.uk/media//94807/Page%208%20and%209%20Enviro%20Issue%2013.pdf |archive-date=27 March 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Traffic ===\nIn 1791 the mines at Worsley produced {{convert|100282|LT}} of coal, {{convert|60461|LT}} of which were \"sold down the navigation\";<ref name=chal37/> {{convert|12000|LT}} of [[Halite|rocksalt]] was also transported from [[Cheshire]].  Sales of coal were \u00a319,455, and nearly \u00a330,000 was earned from other cargoes.  Passenger traffic in 1791 brought in receipts of \u00a33,781.<ref name=chal37/>\n\nThe canal also carried passengers and was in keen competition with the Mersey and Irwell Navigation Company (M&IN).  The journey down river by the latter route took eight hours (nine hours in the up direction) while the journey on the Bridgewater canal took nine hours each way.  Fares were similar but the Bridgewater route was said to be \"more picturesque\".{{sfn|Starkey|1990|p=130|ps=}} [[Boating]] men also used the canal.  They lifted their small lightweight boats out of the M&IN at Runcorn, and carried them a short distance up the steep streets onto the Bridgewater Canal.{{sfn|Corbett|1974|p=40|ps=}}\n\nBarges on the canal continued to be towed by horses until the middle of the 19th century, when they were replaced by steam-powered boats after a fatal epidemic spread through the horse population. The \"dense smoke\" produced by the steam barges and their \"harsh unnecessary whistling\" proved unpopular with some local residents, who also began to suffer from a condition known as canal throat, \"no doubt caused by the foul emanations given off by its [the Bridgewater Canal's] horribly filthy water\".<ref name=AspinP48>{{Harvnb|Aspin|1995|p=48}}</ref>\n\nThe canal carried commercial freight traffic until 1975; the last regular cargo was grain from Liverpool to Manchester for BOCM. It is now used mainly by pleasure craft and hosts two [[sport rowing|rowing]] clubs&nbsp;\u2013 Trafford Rowing Club and Manchester University Boat Club.\n\n== Bridgewater Trustees ==\nThe Duke of Bridgewater died on 8 March 1803.  By his will the income from the canal was to be paid to his nephew [[George Leveson-Gower, 1st Duke of Sutherland|George Leveson-Gower]], the Marquess of Stafford (later the 1st Duke of Sutherland).  On his death it was to go to Stafford's second son [[Francis Egerton, 1st Earl of Ellesmere|Francis]], provided he changed his name to Egerton; and then to his heirs and successors. The management of the company was placed in the hands of three trustees.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=xviii\u2013xix}}</ref> These were [[Archibald Macdonald|Sir Archibald Macdonald]], who was [[Lord Chief Baron of the Exchequer]], [[Edward Venables-Vernon-Harcourt]], at the time the [[Bishop of Carlisle]] and later the [[Archbishop of York]], and, as Superintendent, [[Robert Haldane Bradshaw]], the Duke's agent. Bradshaw managed the estate, for which he received a salary of \u00a32,000 a year and the use of the duke's mansions at Worsley and Runcorn. The other two trustees had each married nieces of the duke and were \"dummy trustees\".<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|p=6}}</ref>\n[[File:BridgewaterCanalTradeFigures.png|left|thumb|400px|Value of trade carried on the Bridgewater Canal 1806\u201371<ref name=mather358>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=358\u2013359}}</ref>]]\nDuring the time the canal was administered by the Bridgewater Trustees, it made a profit every year.<ref name=mather358/>  Until his retirement in 1834, the administration was carried out entirely by Bradshaw. It has been calculated that the average annual profit between 1806 and 1826 was of the order of 13 per cent, and in 1824, the best year, it was 23 per cent.{{sfn|Mather|1970|p=7|ps=}}  Bradshaw found it difficult to delegate, and complained of being over-worked, but he was also regarded as being a \"formidable bargainer\".{{sfn|Mather|1970|pp=10\u201311|ps=}} In 1805 he was approached by the proprietors of the nearby [[Manchester Bolton & Bury Canal]] to resolve a dispute with a Salford landowner, but his response was delayed.<ref name=\"Tomlinsonp33\"/> In 1810 there was a general agreement with the [[Mersey and Irwell Navigation]] Company (M&IN) to simultaneously raise freight charges. However any cooperation between the two companies was short-lived and by 1812 the Mersey and Irwell had reduced their charges. Further competition was to come from other carriers who used the canal; in 1824 the traffic carried by private companies exceeded that carried by the Trustees for the first time. However, in time more profit came from \"tonnage traffic\" (that carried by private companies) than from the Bridgewater's own carriage of freight.{{sfn|Mather|1970|pp=12\u201315|ps=}} Bradshaw's administration saw increased deterioration of the fabric of the canal, the locks, docks and warehouses. The undertakings were starved of capital largely owing to inadequate provision for it in the duke's will.{{sfnp|Mather|1970|pp=21\u201323|ps=}} There were also problems caused by silting around the entrance to the Mersey and by the changing channels of the river itself.{{sfn|Mather|1970|pp=17, 20|ps=}}\n\nDuring the 1820s there was increased dissatisfaction with the canals. They did not cope well with increasing volumes of cargo, and they were perceived as monopolistic, and the preserve of the landed gentry class.  There was increased interest in the possibility of railway construction.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=27\u201333}}</ref>  The possible construction of a railway between Liverpool and Manchester was vigorously opposed by Bradshaw, who refused railway surveyors access to land owned by the Trustees.  When the first [[Bill (proposed law)|bill]] was presented to parliament in 1825, the Trustees opposed and it was overthrown.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=36\u201337}}</ref> However, later in the year Lord Stafford, possibly persuaded to do so by [[William Huskisson]], invested \u00a3100,000 (one-fifth of the required capital), in the [[Liverpool and Manchester Railway]].  Following this the Trustees withdrew their opposition to the construction of the railway; they did not petition against the second bill, which was passed in 1826.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=38\u201341}}</ref> At the same time as he made his investment in the railway, Lord Stafford advanced \u00a340,000 for improvements to the canal. This was spent mainly on a second line of locks at Runcorn, which were completed in 1828, plus new warehouses at Manchester and Liverpool.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=54\u201355}}</ref>  The additional line of locks cost \u00a335,000<ref name=\"Starkeyp179\">{{Harvnb|Starkey|1990|p=179}}</ref> and was used for traffic heading to Manchester, while the old line was used for traffic passing down to the Mersey.<ref>{{Harvnb|Starkey|1983|p=173}}</ref>\n\nIn 1830 the new railway opened and by the end of the year was carrying freight. Bradshaw immediately went into competition by lowering the rates of carriage on the canal and by offering improved terms to the private carriers. By so doing he managed to maintain the volume of traffic carried by the canal, both freight and passengers, at a time when the country was suffering a trade [[Depression (economics)|depression]]. However Bradshaw's tactics led to a sharp decline in profits. At the same time costs were rising, partly due to the use of steamboats on the Mersey. Further competition came with the opening of the [[Macclesfield Canal]] in 1831 which gave separate access to Manchester from the Midlands.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=57\u201361}}</ref> In November 1831 Bradshaw suffered a [[stroke]], as a result of which he lost the use of his left arm and leg, and there is evidence that it also impaired his judgement.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=80\u201382, 85}}</ref>\n\nMatters came to a head in 1833, the year in which the canal made its lowest profit since the death of the Duke.<ref name=mather358/> On 19&nbsp;July the Marquess of Stafford (now the 1st Duke of Sutherland) died and the profits from the canal passed to Francis Egerton. On 25&nbsp;September Bradshaw's son, [[James Bradshaw (MP for Brackley)|Captain James Bradshaw]], who had been acting as a deputy superintendent to the Trustees, and who had been expected to succeed his father as Superintendent, committed suicide. The agent for both Francis Egerton and his older brother, who was now the [[George Sutherland-Leveson-Gower, 2nd Duke of Sutherland|2nd Duke of Sutherland]], was [[James Loch]].<ref name=mather84>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=84\u201386}}</ref>  The events that followed were \"stage-managed by Loch\".<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|p=85}}</ref> He reported to Francis Egerton that Bradshaw was no longer fit to be Superintendent, and then persuaded Bradshaw to retire on his full salary. It had been expected that he would appoint his other son, William Rigby Bradshaw, as his successor, but Loch persuaded him to appoint James Sothern in the position; Sothern had been the principal agent of the Trust since December 1832. He took over the position of Superintendent on 3&nbsp;February 1834.<ref name=mather84/>  The appointment of Sothern was not a success. Charges were made against him of dishonesty and of nepotism. He entered into disputes and disagreements with Loch, with Francis Egerton, and with the other two trustees. (Sir Archibald Macdonald had died in 1826; by this time his place had been taken by the [[William Courtenay, 10th Earl of Devon|10th Earl of Devon]]). To avoid a costly lawsuit, at the end of 1836 Sothern agreed to retire on various conditions which included receipt of \u00a345,000. On 1&nbsp;March 1837, he was succeeded as Superintendent by James Loch.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=87\u201397}}</ref>\n\nLoch was extremely busy and did not have time to deal with the detailed administration of the Trust. He therefore looked for a deputy to take on these duties. His first choice was Richard Smith who was the mine agent to the Trustees of the [[John Ward, 1st Earl of Dudley|1st Earl of Dudley]]. However this was perceived as poaching and it led to such controversy that Smith declined the offer and recommended his son, [[George Samuel Fereday Smith]] for the post. Fereday Smith was appointed as Deputy Superintendent in March 1837 on a salary of \u00a3600 a year, half of the salary which had been offered to his father.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=98\u201399}}</ref> Loch immediately undertook a reorganisation of the administration and efficiency of the business,<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=100\u2013102}}</ref> restored the agreement with the Old Quay Company to raise freight charges, and improved the facilities for passengers, including the introduction of \"swift boats\".<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=105\u2013110}}</ref>  By 1837, the Trustees employed around 3,000&nbsp;people (including those working in the colliery and in Worsley Yard), making it one of the largest employers in the country at the time.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=1\u20132}}</ref> Since the death of the Duke the amount of freight carried by the canal had almost trebled; in 1803 it carried {{convert|334495|LT}} of goods and in 1836 {{convert|968795|LT}}.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|p=3}}</ref>\n\nIn 1843 a new dock, the Francis Dock, was opened at Runcorn.<ref name=\"Starkeyp179\"/> The late 1830s and early 1840s had seen increased competition between the Bridgewater Canal on the one hand, and other canal companies and the railways on the other.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=121\u2013151}}</ref> The most dangerous of the rivals was the Mersey and Irwell Navigation Company who started to reduce their rates again in 1840. This led to a price war between the two canal companies and the Liverpool and Manchester Railway, who had previously cooperated on rates.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=152\u2013155}}</ref>  Eventually, in desperation, the Bridgewater Trustees bought the Mersey and Irwell and took over its ownership on 1 January 1844.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=162\u2013163}}</ref> During the same year competition with other canals was further reduced by agreements made with the [[Ellesmere Canal|Ellesmere and Chester Canal]] Company and with the Anderton Carrying Company.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=167\u2013169}}</ref>  In 1844 the canal made a profit of \u00a376,410, the second highest during the time it was administered by the Trustees.<ref name=mather358/>\n\nHaving seen off competition from other canal companies, the next major threat was to come from the railways.  This was the period in the mid-1840s known as the [[Railway Mania]].  The railways competed with the canals in three ways; by building, or threatening to build, new lines which would be in direct competition with the canals; by amalgamation into giant companies (such as the [[Midland Railway|Midland]] and the [[London and North Western Railway|London and North Western]] companies), which gave them more political power; and by taking over ownership of canal companies.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=176\u2013180}}</ref>  On 13&nbsp;April 1844 ''[[The Times]]'' newspaper reported that the canal was to be emptied of water, and converted into a railway,<ref>{{Citation |title=The Times newspaper: The Bridgewater Canal | url=http://archive.timesonline.co.uk/tol/viewArticle.arc?toDate=1985-12-31&fromDate=1785-01-01&currentPageNumber=1&resultsPerPage=10&sortBy=default&offset=0&viewName=&addFilters=&removeFilters=&addCat=&queryKeywords=bridgewater+canal&sectionId=1040&currPgSmartSet=1&pageId=ARCHIVE-The_Times-1844-04-13-08&articleId=ARCHIVE-The_Times-1844-04-13-08-015&xmlpath=&pubId=17&totalResults=1638&addRefineFilters=&removeRefineFilters=&addRefineCat=&next_Page=false&prev_Page=false&date_dd_From=1&date_mm_From=01&date_yyyy_From=1785&date_dd_to_range=31&date_mm_to_range=12&date_yyyy_to_range=1985&date_dd_from_precise=1&date_mm_from_precise=01&date_yyyy_from_precise=1785&isDateSearch=false&dateSearchType=range&refineQuerykeywordText= |date=13 April 1844|accessdate=19 July 2008 | location=London |first1=Rachel |last1=Sylvester |first2=Sam |last2=Coates}}</ref> although nothing came of this scheme. In 1845, in return for concessions, the Trustees supported the [[Grand Junction Railway]] in its campaign to build a more direct line to Liverpool, which crossed the Mersey over a bridge at Runcorn Gap.  However the bill was overthrown in the House of Lords.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=182\u2013183}}</ref>  Competition from the railways and other canals led to a decline in the trading and the profits between 1845 and 1848, but there was no \"disastrous collapse\".<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|p=189}}</ref>  During this time the Trustees and their representatives were engaged in vigorous campaigns in Parliament to protect their interests.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=185\u2013189}}</ref>\n\nBy October 1844 a bonding warehouse had been built in Manchester and the first cargo to arrive was announced in a letter to the ''[[Manchester Guardian]],'' later printed in ''[[The Times]]:''\n{{quote|<center>FIRST ARRIVAL IN THE PORT OF MANCHESTER OF A CARGO OF GOODS FOR BOND</center>\nWe have great pleasure in recording the first arrival in the Port of Manchester of a vessel, with an entire cargo of wines and spirits removed in bond, and for bonding in Manchester. The vessel, a flat named the Express, was wholly laden with a valuable cargo of wines and spirits, in all about 40 tons weight, belonging to Mr. William Gibb, spirit merchant, of this town, whose active and long-continued exertions in the struggle to obtain the privilege of bonding for this great and important borough are about to be acknowledged in the form of a substantial mark of respect and gratitude by his fellow-townsmen. The Express arrived from Liverpool on Saturday evening; but it was yesterday morning before she began to unload. She is lying in the Bridgewater Canal, Knott Mill where the Duke's trustees have constructed a large bonding vault, which Mr. Gibb has taken and had licensed for the purpose, and we believe he is now removing his stock of wine and spirits from other ports to Manchester, for the greater convenience of sampling and sale. The lockers, gaugers, and other officers of Customs were in attendance, superintending the unloading of the vessel and thus have commenced the operations of the Manchester Custom-house. It is a gratifying circumstance that a gentleman who took so prominent a part in the struggle to obtain the boon of bonding for Manchester should be the first to enjoy the fruits of its success. We hope ere long to record the general operation of the system; though it will require a little time, perhaps, as it must have a beginning. -&nbsp;''Manchester Guardian''<ref>{{citation |last=author unknown |title=First arrival in the Port of Manchester of a cargo of goods for bond |newspaper=The Times |page=6 |date=10 October 1844}}\n</ref>|}}\n\nHowever, this venture was less successful than expected, as is evidenced by a letter to ''[[The Observer]]'' later that year, also printed in ''The Times'':\n\n{{quote|<center>MANCHESTER A BONDING PORT</center> After the pressing demands which have been made by some of our principal manufacturing towns for the privileges of inland bonded warehouses for goods subject to Customs duties, it would naturally be supposed that the formation of a Custom-house establishment at Manchester would have occasioned a vast quantity of business in that extensive seat of British manufacturers; but we are informed that the result is very different from what had been expected. Although the system has been introduced into Manchester only as an experiment and a large establishment has been formed entirely of old and experienced officers; under the impression that the extent of business there would require the constant services of well tried men, we believe that, up to the present period, little trade has passed through the Manchester Custom-house and the officers' duties are nearly approaching to a sinecure. The total annual expense of this establishment, exclusive of that for the Custom-house and warehouse is \u00a32,620. The town council of the borough of Manchester, however, are made liable, under the act of the 7th and 8th of Victoria cap 81, to the charges of maintaining this establishment, and the public are thereby exonerated from the expense. <br />-&nbsp;''Observer''<ref>{{citation |last=author unknown |title=Manchester a bonding port |newspaper=The Times |page=2 |date= 3 December 1844}}</ref>|}}\n\nBetween 1849 and 1851 the competition between the Trustees and the railway companies intensified.  Agreements and alliances were made and broken.  Their major opponents were the London and North Western Railway and the [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]] who reduced tariffs and took business away from the canals.  For the first time the railways carried more trade between Liverpool and the towns of central Lancashire than the canals.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=195\u2013225}}</ref>  The value of the traffic carried by the Bridgewater Canal in 1851 was the lowest in the time it was administered by the Trustees.<ref name=mather358/>  In 1851 the Earl of Ellesmere hosted [[Royal visits to Manchester and Salford during the reign of Queen Victoria|a visit to Manchester]] by [[Queen Victoria]] and [[Albert, Prince Consort|Prince Albert]].  They stayed at Worsley Hall, with a view of the canal, and were given a trip between [[Patricroft railway station]] and Worsley Hall, on state barges.  Large crowds had gathered to cheer the royal party, which apparently frightened the horses drawing the barge so much that they fell into the canal.<ref>{{Harvnb|Corbett|1974|p=43}}</ref>\n\nThe Trustees spent much time between 1851 and 1855 in negotiations to ease the competition, especially that from the London and North Western Railway.  The most likely allies seemed to be other railway companies, including the [[Shrewsbury and Birmingham Railway|Shrewsbury and Birmingham]] and the [[Shrewsbury to Chester Line|Shrewsbury and Chester]] railway companies, and the Great Western Railway.  Of these, the most likely seemed to be the Great Western Railway who, in their concern to expand northwards were willing to help the Trustees with the carriage of their traffic to the south.  However years of negotiations came to no agreement and, in the end, the Trustees' railway deal was done with the London and North Western Railway, who agreed to cooperate with the onward passage of the Trustees' traffic.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=226\u2013256}}</ref>\n\nOn 28&nbsp;June 1855 James Loch, the Superintendent, died and was succeeded by [[Algernon Egerton|Hon. Algernon Fulke Egerton]], Lord Ellesmere's third son.  He was then aged 29, and had been educated at [[Harrow School|Harrow]] and [[Christ Church, Oxford]]; he had been destined for a political life and had no experience of managing coal mines or canals.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|p=267}}</ref>  Since James Loch had been appointed, he had been mainly in control of the management of the Trustees, assisted by his son [[George Loch]].  During this time the role of Fereday Smith had been diminished; initially appointed as Deputy Superintendent, his position was reduced to that of Principal Agent in 1845.  With the arrival of the inexperienced Algernon Egerton, Fereday Smith had a much greater say in the management.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=268\u2013269}}</ref>  During the previous four years the Lochs had been reluctant to invest in improvements to the canal or Runcorn Dock, despite the increasing demand for the passage of goods through the dock, and the profits made during these years became stagnant.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=259\u2013267}}</ref>  Fereday Smith had been keen on expansion<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|p=260}}</ref> and now his opportunity came.  He first reduced the top-heavy administration of the Trust,<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=269\u2013270}}</ref> and then took on the planning of the expansion of the business.  The [[Steamboat|steamers]] owned by the Trustees had been neglected and were in a poor state; these were repaired or sold.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=272\u2013273}}</ref>\n\nGeorge Loch, who had been opposed to using the Trustees' investments for improvements to the canals or docks, died in 1857. Between 1857 and 1872 the Trustees provided more capital for improvements from their own resources than at any previous time.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|p=280}}</ref>  The [[Runcorn and Weston Canal]] was built in 1858\u201359, providing a connection between Runcorn Docks and the [[River Weaver|Weaver Navigation]].  A new [[half tide dock]], the [[Port of Runcorn#Runcorn Docks|Alfred Dock]] was opened at Runcorn in 1860.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|p=281}}</ref>  [[Electric telegraph]] was installed in 1861\u201362.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|p=288}}</ref>\n\nIn 1862 the 2nd&nbsp;Earl of Ellesmere died and his son and heir, the [[Francis Egerton, 3rd Earl of Ellesmere|3rd&nbsp;Earl]] was a [[Minor (law)|minor]], aged 15.  This gave Algernon Egerton even more power to invest the profits of the company in developments.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=280\u2013281}}</ref>  Negotiations were made to increase sea-borne trade, both British and foreign, through the canal.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=283\u2013285}}</ref>  Building started on a new dock at Runcorn in 1867. Work was carried out in the Mersey estuary around the docks to improve access for vessels.  Some of this was carried out in conjunction with the London and North Western Railway who were building a [[Runcorn Railway Bridge|bridge]] across Runcorn Gap to take their line from Weaver Junction to Liverpool; the railway paid half the cost of the improvements, amounting to about \u00a320,000 (\u00a3{{Formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|20000|1867|r=-4}}|0}} today).{{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}}<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=285\u2013286}}</ref>  Improvements were made to the Trustees' facilities at Liverpool, to the Mersey and Irwell Navigation and to the Bridgewater Canal itself.<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=287\u2013291}}</ref>  Agreements were made with the railway companies to cooperate on the transit of goods and the rates of carriage<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|pp=292\u2013304}}</ref> and \"the Trustees' fortunes entered a calmer phase\".<ref>{{Harvnb|Mather|1970|p=299}}</ref>\n\n== Subsequent owners ==\n[[File:Barton Swing Aqueduct.jpg|thumb|right|Barton Swing Aqueduct, built to replace the original aqueduct during construction of the [[Manchester Ship Canal]]]]\nIn 1872 the Bridgewater Navigation Company Ltd was formed, and on Monday 9 September the canal was purchased in the names of [[Edward Watkin|Sir Edward William Watkin]] and William Philip Price, respectively chairmen of the [[Manchester, Sheffield and Lincolnshire Railway]] and the [[Midland Railway]] for \u00a31,120,000.<ref>{{citation |title=The Times newspaper: The Bridgewater Canal | url=http://archive.timesonline.co.uk/tol/viewArticle.arc?toDate=1985-12-31&fromDate=1785-01-01&currentPageNumber=1&resultsPerPage=10&sortBy=default&offset=0&viewName=&addFilters=&removeFilters=&addCat=&queryKeywords=bridgewater+canal&sectionId=1040&currPgSmartSet=1&pageId=ARCHIVE-The_Times-1872-09-09-10&articleId=ARCHIVE-The_Times-1872-09-09-10-003&xmlpath=&pubId=17&totalResults=1638&addRefineFilters=&removeRefineFilters=&addRefineCat=&next_Page=false&prev_Page=false&date_dd_From=1&date_mm_From=01&date_yyyy_From=1785&date_dd_to_range=31&date_mm_to_range=12&date_yyyy_to_range=1985&date_dd_from_precise=1&date_mm_from_precise=01&date_yyyy_from_precise=1785&isDateSearch=false&dateSearchType=range&refineQuerykeywordText= |date=9 September 1872|accessdate=19 July 2008 |location=London |first1=Rachel |last1=Sylvester |first2=Sam |last2=Coates}}</ref>{{sfn|Mather|1970|pp=334\u2013335|ps=}}  The canal was sold again in 1885, when the [[Manchester Ship Canal]] Company paid the Bridgewater Navigation Company \u00a31,710,000 for all their property.<ref>{{citation |title=Bridgewater Canal History, 1872 - Change and Consolidation |url=http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/timeline9.html |publisher=The Manchester Ship Canal Company |accessdate=2 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121225344/http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/timeline9.html |archivedate=21 November 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>  The construction of the ship canal forced the removal of Barton Aqueduct and the construction of [[Barton Swing Aqueduct]], as the former was too low for the vessels which would use the new canal.  In 1907 The Manchester Ship Canal (Bridgewater Canal) Act 1907 was passed, permitting coal mining near the canal between Monton Bridge and Leigh, in exchange for which the mine owners were obliged to pay the associated costs of keeping the canal open and navigable.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Manchester Ship Canal (Bridgewater Canal) Act 1907 (Amendment) Order 1996 |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/1996/1484/note/made |publisher=The National Archives |accessdate=23 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1923 Bridgewater Estates Ltd was formed to acquire the [[Earl of Ellesmere|Ellesmere family]] estate in Worsley. In 1984 Bridgewater Estates Ltd was purchased by a subsidiary of [[Peel Group|Peel Holdings]]. In 1987 Highams acquired a majority shareholding of the Manchester Ship Canal Company (subsequently the shares held by Highams were transferred to Peel Holdings).  In 1994 the Manchester Ship Canal Company became a wholly owned subsidiary of the Peel Holdings group. In 2004 ownership of the Manchester Ship Canal Company was transferred to the Peel Ports group.<ref>{{citation |title=Bridgewater Canal History, 1920s to present day |url=http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/timeline11.html |publisher=The Manchester Ship Canal Company |accessdate=2 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121221130/http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/timeline11.html |archivedate=21 November 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Current status ==\n[[File:Barton-upon-Irwell 11.05.02R.jpg|thumb|right|Aerial view of Barton-on-Irwell in 2002 looking SE showing the [[Barton Swing Aqueduct]] over the ship canal (left) and the [[Barton Road Swing Bridge]] (right)]]\n\nThe Bridgewater is often wrongly argued to be the first true canal in England, as it relied upon existing watercourses as sources of water rather than as navigable routes.<ref>{{Citation|title=In Brief|url=http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/history.html|publisher=The Manchester Ship Canal Company|accessdate=5 December 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705023435/http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/history.html|archivedate=5 July 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>The [[Sankey Canal|Sankey Brook Navigation]] also has a claim to be the first modern British canal.</ref>  It now terminates in Runcorn basin, just before the disused flight of 10 locks<ref name=Runcornlockssociety>{{Citation|title=Runcorn Locks Restoration Society |url=http://www.runcornlocks.org.uk/ |accessdate=14 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080705104636/http://www.runcornlocks.org.uk/ |archivedate=5 July 2008 }}</ref> which (before the approach road to the [[Silver Jubilee Bridge]] was built) used to lower the canal to the Runcorn Docks on the River Mersey and later, to the Manchester Ship Canal. The old line of locks in Runcorn fell into disuse in the late 1930s, and they were closed under the Ship Canal Act of 1949 and filled in. The Ship Canal Act of 1966 allowed the closure and filling in of the newer line of locks.<ref>{{Harvnb|Starkey|1983|p=206}}</ref>  The gates from this flight of locks were removed and installed at Devizes on the [[Kennet and Avon Canal]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}  The Duke's warehouse in Manchester was demolished in 1960.<ref name=pb15/>\n\nThe canal has suffered three breaches; one soon after opening, another in 1971 near the [[River Bollin]] aqueduct,<ref name=BollinLeak>{{Citation |title=Maintaining an Ageing Network |publisher=Manchester Ship Canal Company |url=http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/timeline12.html |accessdate=2 July 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121221942/http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/timeline12.html |archivedate=21 November 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and another in the summer of 2005 when a sluice gate failed in Manchester.<ref name=SluiceFailure>{{Citation | title=Bridgewater Canal News&nbsp;\u2014 Sluice Failure Drains Canal | url=http://www.penninewaterways.co.uk/news19.htm | publisher = Pennine Waterways | accessdate = 18 September 2008 | format= \u2013 <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=intitle%3ABridgewater+Canal+News%26nbsp%3B%E2%80%94+Sluice+Failure+Drains+Canal&as_publication=&as_ylo=&as_yhi=&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup>|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070622083851/http://www.penninewaterways.co.uk/news19.htm |archivedate = 22 June 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Crane (machine)|Cranes]] are located at intervals along the canal's length to allow boards to be dropped into slots in the banks.  These allow sections of the canal to be isolated in the event of a leak.\n\nThe canal now forms an integral part of the [[Cheshire Ring]] network of canals.<ref>{{Citation | title = Information about Bridgewater Canal | url = http://www.waterscape.com/canals-and-rivers/bridgewater-canal | publisher = British Waterways | accessdate = 5 December 2008 }}</ref>  Pleasure craft have been allowed on the canal since 1952.<ref name=Penninewaterways/>\n\nThe new road crossing of the Mersey now under construction may allow a realignment of the bridge approach road and the complete restoration of the original flight of locks<ref>{{Citation|title=Bridgewater Canal&nbsp;\u2013 Runcorn Locks (Under Restoration)|url=http://www.waterways.org.uk/Waterways/PrincipalNavigations/BridgewaterCanalRuncornLocksUnderRestoration|publisher=The Inland Waterways Association, 2006|accessdate=14 August 2008|format= \u2013 <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=intitle%3ABridgewater+Canal%26nbsp%3B%E2%80%93+Runcorn+Locks+%28Under+Restoration%29&as_publication=&as_ylo=&as_yhi=&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup>|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071109223556/http://www.waterways.org.uk/Waterways/PrincipalNavigations/BridgewaterCanalRuncornLocksUnderRestoration |archivedate = 9 November 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 thus re-opening the link to Runcorn Docks, the Runcorn and Weston Canal, the River Mersey, the Manchester Ship Canal, and the River Weaver.  This would create a new ring route for leisure boats involving the Trent and Mersey Canal, the [[Anderton Boat Lift]] and the River Weaver.<ref name=Runcornlockssociety/>\n\nThe [[Hulme Locks Branch Canal]] in Manchester is now disused, and on 26 May 1995 was replaced by the nearby Pomona Lock.\n\n=== Bridgewater Way ===\nThe Bridgewater Way is a scheme to redevelop the canal and make it more accessible to users, particularly cyclists. The 40-mile development, which includes a new towpath, will form part of the National Cycle and Footpath Network as Regional Route number 82.<ref name=Bridgewaterway>{{Citation | title = Bridgewater Brochure 2008 | url = http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/bridgewaterbrochure.pdf | format = PDF | publisher = The Bridgewater Canal Trust | accessdate = 8 August 2008 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081121223905/http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/bridgewaterbrochure.pdf | archivedate = 21 November 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|United Kingdom|Transport|Cheshire}}\n* [[Canals of the United Kingdom]]\n* [[History of the British canal system]]\n\n== References ==\n===Notes===\n{{notelist|notes=}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{citation |title=Reader's Digest Library of Modern Knowledge |publisher=[[Reader's Digest]] |year=1978}}\n* {{citation |title=The Bridgewater Canal Handbook |publisher=Ed. J. Burrow & Co. |year= |isbn=}}\n:Although no details of author and date are given, this is likely to be a reliable source as it was published for the [[Manchester Ship Canal]] Company in 1973 or later (a picture of the reopening of the canal is on the cover).\n* {{citation |last=Aspin |first=Chris |title=The First industrial Society: Lancashire 1750\u20131850 |year=1995 |publisher=Carnegie Publishing |isbn=1-85936-016-5}}\n* {{citation |last=Chaloner |first=William Henry |title=People and Industries |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xq7BFVtwANcC |year=1963 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=0-7146-1284-7}}\n* {{citation |last=Collins |first=Arthur |title=Collins's peerage of England; genealogical, biographical, and historical |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r_M6AAAAIAAJ |publisher=F. C. and J. Rivington, Otridge and Son |year=1812}}\n* {{citation |last=Corbett |first=John |title=Pleasant Reminiscences of the Nineteenth Century and Suggestions for Improvements in the Twentieth. |publisher=E. J. Morton |year=1974 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=b0KEHwAACAAJ |isbn=0-85972-006-3}}\n*{{citation |last=Hayes |first=Geoffrey |title=Collieries and their Railways in the Manchester Coalfields |publisher=Landmark |year=2004 |isbn=1-84306-135-X}}\n* {{citation |last=Kindleberger |first=Charles Poor |title=A Financial History of Western Europe |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PFgIE7_eYwwC |publisher=Oxford University Press US |year=1993 |isbn=0-19-507738-5}}\n* {{citation |last=Mather |first=F. A. |title=After the Canal Duke |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1970 |isbn=}}\n* {{citation |last=Mullineux |first=Frank |date=1959 |title=The Duke of Bridgewater's Canal |publisher=Eccles and District History Society.}}\n* {{citation |last=Nickson |first=Charles |title=History of Runcorn  |publisher=Mackie & Co. |year=1887}}\n* {{citation |last=Parkinson-Bailey |first=John |title=Manchester: An Architectural History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ush5WC9BM_gC |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=0-7190-5606-3 |year=2000}}\n* {{citation |last=Pickering |first=Danby |title=The Statutes at Large: From the Magna Charta, to the End of the Eleventh Parliament of Great Britain, Anno 1761 {continued to 1807} |publisher=J Bentham |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GqwuAAAAIAAJ |year=1807}}\n* {{citation |last=Priestley |first=Joseph |title=Historical Account of the Navigable Rivers, Canals, and Railways of Great Britain |publisher=Longman, Green |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eUqIucVmZjwC |year=1831}}\n* {{citation |last=Skempton |first=Sir Alec |title=A Biographical Dictionary of Civil Engineers in Great Britain and Ireland: 1500 to 1830 |publisher=Thomas Telford |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jeOMfpYMOtYC |year=2002 |isbn=0-7277-2939-X}}\n* {{citation |last=Smiles |first=Samuel | title= Lives of the Engineers |publisher=Read Books |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PdmctboVgsYC |year=2006 |isbn=1-4067-9868-1}}\n* {{citation |last=Starkey |first=H. F. |title =Schooner Port: Two Centuries of Upper Mersey Sail  |publisher=G. W. & A. Hesketh  |year=1983 |isbn=0-905777-34-4}}\n* {{citation |last=Starkey |first=H. F. |title=Old Runcorn |publisher=Halton Borough Council |year=1990 |isbn=}}\n* {{citation |last=Sweeney |first=D. J. |title=A Lancashire Triangle Part Two |publisher=Triangle Publishing |year=1997 |isbn=0-9529333-2-2}}\n* {{citation |last=Timbs |first=John |title=Stories of Inventors and Discoverers in Science and the Useful Arts: A Book for Old and Young |year=1860 |publisher=Harper & Brothers}}\n* {{citation|last=Tomlinson |first=Victor I. |title=The Manchester Bolton And Bury Canal |publisher=The Manchester Bolton & Bury Canal Society |url=http://www.mbbcs.org.uk/society/sales.htm |year=1991 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081010144006/http://www.mbbcs.org.uk/society/sales.htm |archivedate=2008-10-10 }}\n* {{citation |last=Ware |first=Michael E. |title=Britain's lost waterways |year=1989 |publisher=Moorland |isbn=0-86190-327-7}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=Y7c2rVtmyPcC James Brindley: An Illustrated Life of James Brindley, 1716\u20131772]\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category-inline|Bridgewater Canal}}\n* [http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/ Bridgewater Canal website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071117233235/http://www.bridgewatercanal.co.uk/location2.html Bridgewater Canal map]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040805130654/http://www.penninewaterways.co.uk/bridgewater/index.htm Website with description and photographs]\n* [http://www.isd.salford.ac.uk/library/resources/special/duke-bridgewater.xml Duke of Bridgewater Archive from the University of Salford site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060924230857/http://www.d.lane.btinternet.co.uk/canal.html Duke of Bridgewater's Underground Canal at Worsley]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070403183315/http://www.agcm.org.uk/museum.shtml Astley Green Colliery Museum]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071116063128/http://www.shipcanal.co.uk/ Manchester Ship Canal Company website]\n\n<!--spacing-->\n\n{{Canals of Britain}}\n\n[[Category:Canals in England]]\n[[Category:Canals in Trafford]]\n[[Category:Canals in Warrington]]\n[[Category:Canals in the Metropolitan Borough of Wigan]]\n[[Category:Industrial Revolution]]\n[[Category:Canals in Cheshire]]\n[[Category:Irwell Valley]]\n[[Category:Canals opened in 1761]]\n[[Category:1761 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "Dave.Dunford", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBridgewater Way:convert template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bridgewater_Canal"}
{"title_page": "Glucocorticoid remediable aldosteronism", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Glucocorticoid remediable aldosteronism\n| synonyms        = GRA\n| image           = \n| caption         = \n| pronounce       = \n| field           = [[Endocrinology]]\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n\n'''Glucocorticoid remediable aldosteronism''' also describable as ''aldosterone synthase hyperactivity'', is an [[autosomal dominant]] disorder in which the increase in [[aldosterone]] secretion produced by [[ACTH]] is no longer transient.\n\nIt is a cause of [[primary hyperaldosteronism]].<ref name=\"pmid17277347\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Vonend O, Altenhenne C, B\u00fcchner NJ, etal |title=A German family with glucocorticoid-remediable aldosteronism |journal=Nephrol. Dial. Transplant. |volume=22 |issue=4 |pages=1123\u201330 |date=April 2007 |pmid=17277347 |doi=10.1093/ndt/gfl706}}</ref>\n\n==Symptoms==\nPatients with GRA may be [[asymptomatic]], but the following symptoms can be present:\n\n* [[Fatigue (physical)|Fatigue]]\n* [[Headache]]\n* [[High blood pressure]]\n* [[Hypokalemia]]\n* Intermittent or temporary [[paralysis]]\n* [[Muscle spasms]]\n* [[Muscle weakness]]\n* [[Numbness]]\n* [[Polyuria]]\n* [[Polydipsia]]\n* Tingling\n* [[Hypernatraemia]]\n* [[Metabolic alkalosis]]\n\n==Normal Physiology==\n[[File:Steroidogenesis.svg|thumb|Right|360px|[[Steroidogenesis]], showing aldosterone synthase at right.]]\n{{main | Aldosterone synthase}}\n\n[[Aldosterone synthase]] is a [[steroid]] [[hydroxylase]] [[cytochrome P450]] oxidase enzyme involved in the generation of [[aldosterone]]. It is localized to the [[mitochondrial]] inner membrane. The enzyme has steroid [[18-hydroxylase]] activity to synthesize [[aldosterone]] and other steroids. Aldosterone synthase is found within the [[zona glomerulosa]] at the outer edge of the [[adrenal cortex]]. Aldosterone synthase normally is not ACTH sensitive, and only activated by [[angiotensin II]].\n\nAldosterone causes the [[tubules]] of the [[kidneys]] to retain [[sodium]] and [[water]]. This increases the volume of fluid in the body, and drives up [[blood pressure]].\n\nSteroid hormones are synthesized from [[cholesterol]] within the [[adrenal cortex]]. [[Aldosterone]] and [[corticosterone]] share the first part of their biosynthetic pathway. The last part is either mediated by the aldosterone synthase (for aldosterone) or by the [[11\u03b2-hydroxylase]] (for [[corticosterone]]).\n\n:'''[[Steroid metabolism|Aldosterone synthesis]] is stimulated by several factors:'''\n::by increase in the plasma concentration of [[angiotensin III]].\n::by increased plasma [[angiotensin II]], [[ACTH]], or [[potassium]] levels.\n::The [[ACTH stimulation test]] is sometimes used to stimulate the production of aldosterone along with [[cortisol]] to determine if primary or secondary [[adrenal insufficiency]] is present.\n::by plasma [[acidosis]].\n::by the [[Mechanoreceptors|stretch receptors]] located in the [[Atrium (heart)|atria]] of the [[heart]].\n::by [[adrenoglomerulotropin]], a [[lipid]] factor, obtained from [[pineal]] extracts. It selectively stimulates secretion of aldosterone.\n::The secretion of aldosterone has a [[diurnal rhythm]].\n\n:'''Control of aldosterone release from the adrenal cortex:'''\n::*The role of the [[renin\u2013angiotensin system]]:\n:::Angiotensin is involved in regulating aldosterone and is the core regulator. Angiotensin II acts synergistically with potassium.\n::*The role of [[Sympathetic nervous system|sympathetic]] [[nerves]]:\n:::Aldosterone production is also affected to one extent or another by [[nervous control]] which integrates the inverse of [[carotid artery]] pressure, [[pain]], [[Human position|posture]], and probably [[emotion]] ([[anxiety]], [[fear]], and [[hostility]])(including [[surgical stress]]).\n::*The role of [[baroreceptors]]:\n:::Pressure in the [[carotid artery]] decreases aldosterone\n::*The role of the [[juxtaglomerular apparatus]]\n::*The plasma concentration of [[potassium]]:\n:::The amount of aldosterone secreted is a direct function of the serum potassium as probably determined by sensors in the carotid artery.\n::*The plasma concentration of [[sodium]]:\n:::Aldosterone is a function of the [[Multiplicative inverse|inverse]] of the sodium intake as sensed via [[osmotic pressure]].\n::*Miscellaneous regulation:\n:::[[ACTH]], a [[pituitary]] peptide, also has some stimulating effect on aldosterone probably by stimulating [[deoxycorticosterone]] formation which is a [[Precursor (chemistry)|precursor]] of [[aldosterone]].\n:::Aldosterone is increased by [[hemorrhage|blood loss]], [[pregnancy]], and possibly by other circumstances such as [[physical exertion]], [[endotoxin shock]], and [[burn]]s.\n\n:'''Aldosterone [[feedback]]:'''\n::Feedback by aldosterone concentration itself is of a non-morphological character (that is, other than changes in cell number or structure) and is relatively poor, so that electrolyte feedback predominates in the short term.\n\n==Pathophysiology==\nThe [[genes]] encoding [[aldosterone synthase]] and [[Steroid 11\u03b2-hydroxylase|11\u03b2-hydroxylase]] are 95% identical and are close together on [[chromosome 8]]. In individuals with GRA, there is unequal crossing over so that the [[5']] regulatory region of the 11-hydroxylase gene is fused to the coding region of the aldosterone synthase.\n\nThe product of this hybrid gene is [[aldosterone synthase]] that is ACTH-sensitive<ref>Ganong Physiology</ref> in the [[zona fasciculata]] of the adrenal gland.<ref name=\"pmid14667264\">{{cite journal |vauthors=McMahon GT, Dluhy RG |title=Glucocorticoid-remediable aldosteronism |journal=Cardiol Rev |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=44\u20138 |year=2004 |pmid=14667264 |doi=10.1097/01.crd.0000096417.42861.ce }}</ref>\n\nAlthough in normal subjects, ACTH accelerates the [[steroid metabolism|first step of aldosterone synthesis]], [[ACTH]] normally has no effect on the activity of [[aldosterone synthase]]. However, in subjects with glucocorticoid-remediable aldosteronism, ACTH increases the activity of existing [[aldosterone synthase]], resulting in an abnormally high rate of aldosterone synthesis and [[hyperaldosteronism]].\n\n==Diagnosis==\nGenetic testing\n\n==Treatment==\nIn GRA, the hypersecretion of aldosterone and the accompanying [[hypertension]] are remedied when ACTH secretion is suppressed by administering [[glucocorticoids]].\n\n[[Dexamethasone]], [[spironolactone]] and [[eplerenone]] have been used in treatment.<ref name=\"pmid15761539\">{{cite journal |vauthors=McMahon GT, Dluhy RG |title=Glucocorticoid-remediable aldosteronism |journal=Arq Bras Endocrinol Metabol |volume=48 |issue=5 |pages=682\u20136 |date=October 2004 |pmid=15761539 |doi= 10.1590/S0004-27302004000500014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Inborn errors of steroid metabolism]]\n* [[Hyperaldosteronism]]\n* [[Pseudohyperaldosteronism]]\n* [[Apparent mineralocorticoid excess syndrome]]\n* [[Aldosterone]] and [[aldosterone synthase]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| DiseasesDB      = \n| ICD10           = \n| ICD9            = {{ICD9|255.11}}\n| ICDO            = \n| OMIM            = 103900\n| MedlinePlus     = \n| eMedicineSubj   = \n| eMedicineTopic  = \n| MeshID          = \n| ICD10CM         = {{ICD10CM|E26.02}}\n}}\n{{Endocrine pathology}}\n{{Defects of cholesterol and steroid metabolism}}\n\n[[Category:Adrenal gland disorders]]\n[[Category:Cholesterol and steroid metabolism disorders]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Glucocorticoid remediable aldosteronism\n| synonyms        = GRA\n| image           = \n| caption         = \n| pronounce       = \n| field           = [[Endocrinology]]\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n\n'''Glucocorticoid remediable aldosteronism''' also describable as ''aldosterone synthase hyperactivity'', is an [[autosomal dominant]] disorder in which the increase in [[aldosterone]] secretion produced by [[ACTH]] is no longer transient.\n\nIt is a cause of [[primary hyperaldosteronism]].<ref name=\"pmid17277347\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Vonend O, Altenhenne C, B\u00fcchner NJ, etal |title=A German family with glucocorticoid-remediable aldosteronism |journal=Nephrol. Dial. Transplant. |volume=22 |issue=4 |pages=1123\u201330 |date=April 2007 |pmid=17277347 |doi=10.1093/ndt/gfl706}}</ref>\n\n==Symptoms==\nPatients with GRA may be [[asymptomatic]], but the following symptoms can be present:\n\n* [[Fatigue (physical)|Fatigue]]\n* [[Headache]]\n* [[High blood pressure]]\n* [[Hypokalemia]]\n* Intermittent or temporary [[paralysis]]\n* [[Muscle spasms]]\n* [[Muscle weakness]]\n* [[Numbness]]\n* [[Polyuria]]\n* [[Polydipsia]]\n* Tingling\n* [[Hypernatraemia]]\n* [[Metabolic alkalosis]]\n\n==Normal Physiology==\n[[File:Steroidogenesis.svg|thumb|Right|360px|[[Steroidogenesis]], showing aldosterone synthase at right.]]\n{{main | Aldosterone synthase}}\n\n[[Aldosterone synthase]] is a [[steroid]] [[hydroxylase]] [[cytochrome P450]] oxidase enzyme involved in the generation of [[aldosterone]]. It is localized to the [[mitochondrial]] inner membrane. The enzyme has steroid [[18-hydroxylase]] activity to synthesize [[aldosterone]] and other steroids. Aldosterone synthase is found within the [[zona glomerulosa]] at the outer edge of the [[adrenal cortex]]. Aldosterone synthase normally is not ACTH sensitive, and only activated by [[angiotensin II]].\n\nAldosterone causes the [[tubules]] of the [[kidneys]] to retain [[sodium]] and [[water]]. This increases the volume of fluid in the body, and drives up [[blood pressure]].\n\nSteroid hormones are synthesized from [[cholesterol]] within the [[adrenal cortex]]. [[Aldosterone]] and [[corticosterone]] share the first part of their biosynthetic pathway. The last part is either mediated by the aldosterone synthase (for aldosterone) or by the [[11\u03b2-hydroxylase]] (for [[corticosterone]]).\n\n:'''[[Steroid metabolism|Aldosterone synthesis]] is stimulated by several factors:'''\n::by increase in the plasma concentration of [[angiotensin III]].\n::by increased plasma [[angiotensin II]], [[ACTH]], or [[potassium]] levels.\n::The [[ACTH stimulation test]] is sometimes used to stimulate the production of aldosterone along with [[cortisol]] to determine if primary or secondary [[adrenal insufficiency]] is present.\n::by plasma [[acidosis]].\n::by the [[Mechanoreceptors|stretch receptors]] located in the [[Atrium (heart)|atria]] of the [[heart]].\n::by [[adrenoglomerulotropin]], a [[lipid]] factor, obtained from [[pineal]] extracts. It selectively stimulates secretion of aldosterone.\n::The secretion of aldosterone has a [[diurnal rhythm]].\n\n:'''Control of aldosterone release from the adrenal cortex:'''\n::*The role of the [[renin\u2013angiotensin system]]:\n:::Angiotensin is involved in regulating aldosterone and is the core regulator. Angiotensin II acts synergistically with potassium.\n::*The role of [[Sympathetic nervous system|sympathetic]] [[nerves]]:\n:::Aldosterone production is also affected to one extent or another by [[nervous control]] which integrates the inverse of [[carotid artery]] pressure, [[pain]], [[Human position|posture]], and probably [[emotion]] ([[anxiety]], [[fear]], and [[hostility]])(including [[surgical stress]]).\n::*The role of [[baroreceptors]]:\n:::Pressure in the [[carotid artery]] decreases aldosterone\n::*The role of the [[juxtaglomerular apparatus]]\n::*The plasma concentration of [[potassium]]:\n:::The amount of aldosterone secreted is a direct function of the serum potassium as probably determined by sensors in the carotid artery.\n::*The plasma concentration of [[sodium]]:\n:::Aldosterone is a function of the [[Multiplicative inverse|inverse]] of the sodium intake as sensed via [[osmotic pressure]].\n::*Miscellaneous regulation:\n:::[[ACTH]], a [[pituitary]] peptide, also has some stimulating effect on aldosterone probably by stimulating [[deoxycorticosterone]] formation which is a [[Precursor (chemistry)|precursor]] of [[aldosterone]].\n:::Aldosterone is increased by [[hemorrhage|blood loss]], [[pregnancy]], and possibly by other circumstances such as [[physical exertion]], [[endotoxin shock]], and [[burn]]s.\n\n:'''Aldosterone [[feedback]]:'''\n::Feedback by aldosterone concentration itself is of a non-morphological character (that is, other than changes in cell number or structure) and is relatively poor, so that electrolyte feedback predominates in the short term.\n\n==Pathophysiology==\nThe [[genes]] encoding [[aldosterone synthase]] and [[Steroid 11\u03b2-hydroxylase|11\u03b2-hydroxylase]] are 95% identical and are close together on [[chromosome 8]]. In individuals with GRA, there is unequal crossing over so that the [[5']] regulatory region of the 11-hydroxylase gene is fused to the coding region of the aldosterone synthase.\n\nThe product of this hybrid gene is [[aldosterone synthase]] that is ACTH-sensitive<ref>Ganong Physiology</ref> in the [[zona fasciculata]] of the adrenal gland.<ref name=\"pmid14667264\">{{cite journal |vauthors=McMahon GT, Dluhy RG |title=Glucocorticoid-remediable aldosteronism |journal=Cardiol Rev |volume=12 |issue=1 |pages=44\u20138 |year=2004 |pmid=14667264 |doi=10.1097/01.crd.0000096417.42861.ce }}</ref>\n\nAlthough in normal subjects, ACTH accelerates the [[steroid metabolism|first step of aldosterone synthesis]], [[ACTH]] normally has no effect on the activity of [[aldosterone synthase]]. However, in subjects with glucocorticoid-remediable aldosteronism, ACTH increases the activity of existing [[aldosterone synthase]], resulting in an abnormally high rate of aldosterone synthesis and [[hyperaldosteronism]].\n\n==Diagnosis==\nGenetic testing\n\n==Treatment==\nIn GRA, the hypersecretion of aldosterone and the accompanying [[hypertension]] are remedied when ACTH secretion is suppressed by administering [[glucocorticoids]].\n\n[[Dexamethasone]], [[spironolactone]] and [[eplerenone]] have been used in treatment.<ref name=\"pmid15761539\">{{cite journal |vauthors=McMahon GT, Dluhy RG |title=Glucocorticoid-remediable aldosteronism |journal=Arq Bras Endocrinol Metabol |volume=48 |issue=5 |pages=682\u20136 |date=October 2004 |pmid=15761539 |doi= 10.1590/S0004-27302004000500014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Inborn errors of steroid metabolism]]\n* [[Hyperaldosteronism]]\n* [[Pseudohyperaldosteronism]]\n* [[Apparent mineralocorticoid excess syndrome]]\n* [[Aldosterone]] and [[aldosterone synthase]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|  DiseasesDB     = \n|  ICD10          = \n|  ICD9           = {{ICD9|255.11}}\n|  ICDO           = \n|  OMIM           = 103900\n|  MedlinePlus    = \n|  eMedicineSubj  = \n|  eMedicineTopic = \n|  MeshID         = \n}}\n{{Endocrine pathology}}\n{{Defects of cholesterol and steroid metabolism}}\n\n[[Category:Adrenal gland disorders]]\n[[Category:Cholesterol and steroid metabolism disorders]]\n", "name_user": "Dismanet", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding new medical resources.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glucocorticoid_remediable_aldosteronism"}
{"title_page": "Charles Wellbeloved", "text_new": "{{for|the monarch known as Charles the Well-Beloved|Charles VI of France}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Charles Wellbeloved\n|image =YORAG 1202-PCF.jpg\n|caption=Portrait of Charles Wellbeloved\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1769|04|06|df=yes}}\n|birth_place = {{Nowrap|Denmark Street, [[St Giles]], [[London]], England}}\n|death_date = {{Death date and age|1858|08|29|1769|04|06|df=y}} \n|death_place = [[Monkgate]], [[York]], England\n|resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|nationality =\n|citizenship = \n|known_for = \n|alma_mater = \n|height =\n}}\n'''Charles Wellbeloved''' (6 April 1769 \u2013 29 August 1858) was an [[English people|English]] [[Christian Unitarianism|Unitarian]] [[Anglicanism#Anglican divines|divine]] and [[Archaeology|archaeologist]].\n\n==Biography==\nCharles Wellbeloved, only child of John Wellbeloved (1742\u20131787), by his wife Elizabeth Plaw, was born in Denmark Street, [[St Giles, London]], on 6 April 1769, and baptised on 25 April at [[St. Giles-in-the-Fields]]. Owing to domestic unhappiness he was brought up from the age of four by his grandfather, Charles Wellbeloved (1713\u20131782), a country gentleman at [[Mortlake]], Surrey, an Anglican, and the friend and follower of [[John Wesley]]. He got the best part of his early education from a clergyman named Delafosse at Richmond.  In 1783 he was placed with a firm of drapers on Holborn Hill, but only learned \"how to tie up a parcel\".\n\nIn 1785 he became a student at [[Homerton Academy]] under Benjamin Davies.  Among his fellow-students were [[William Field (Unitarian minister)|William Field]] and David Jones (1765\u20131816).  Jones was expelled for heresy in 1786; his opinions had influenced Wellbeloved, who was allowed to finish the session of 1787, but not to return.  In September 1787 he followed Jones to New College, Hackney, under [[Abraham Rees]], the cyclop\u00e6dist, and [[Andrew Kippis]], and subsequently (1789) under [[Thomas Belsham]] and (1790) [[Gilbert Wakefield]].  Here he formed a close friendship with [[Arthur Aikin]], who entered in 1789.  He attended the ministry of [[Richard Price]] (1723\u20131791).  \n\nHe married his wife Ann Kinder (d. 31 January 1823) on 1 July 1793, at St. Mary's, [[Stoke Newington]], with whom he had several children. Their youngest son, [[Robert Wellbeloved]] (15 July 1803&nbsp;\u2013 21 February 1856), married heiress Sarah Scott on 17 February 1830 and assumed the name and arms of Scott on her father's death in 1832.  Robert was a deputy-lieutenant for [[Worcestershire]] and M.P. for [[Walsall]] (1841\u201346).<ref name=\"DNB00\" /> His youngest daughter, Emma (d. 29 July 1842), married (1831) [[James Carter (judge)|Sir James Carter]], chief justice of New Brunswick.<ref name=\"MacNutt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.biographi.ca/009004-119.01-e.php?&id_nbr=4883|title=Carter, Sir James|last=MacNutt|first=William Stewart|work=Dictionary of Canadian Biography Online, vol. 10|publisher=University of Toronto|accessdate=29 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Ecclesiastical career===\nWellbeloved's first sermon was preached at [[Walthamstow]] on 13 November 1791.  Shortly afterwards he received through Michael Maurice, father of [John] [[Frederick Denison Maurice]], an invitation to become assistant to [[Newcome Cappe]] at [[York Unitarian Chapel|St Saviourgate Chapel]], [[York]].  He accepted on 23 January 1792, and began his duties at York on 5 February.  In 1801 he became sole minister on Cappe's death. The chief feature of his [[exegetical]] work was his treatment of prophecy, limiting the range of its prediction, confining that of Hebrew prophecy to the age of its production, and bounding our Lord's predictions by the destruction of Jerusalem. He broke with the Priestley school, rejecting a general resurrection and fixing the last judgment at death. In these and other points he closely followed the system of [[Newcome Cappe]], but his careful avoidance of dogmatism left his pupils free, and none of them followed him into \u2018Cappism.\u2019 Among his coadjutors were [[Theophilus Browne]], [[William Turner (biographer)|William Turner]]<ref>see [[William Turner (1714\u20131794)]]</ref> and William Hincks.<ref>[see under , [[Robert Dix Hincks]]]</ref> From 1810 he had the invaluable co-operation of [[John Kenrick (historian)|John Kenrick]], who married his elder daughter L\u00e6titia.\n\nIn 1794 he began to take pupils into a Sunday school he had founded. He was invited in November 1797 (after Belsham had declined) to succeed [[Thomas Barnes (Unitarian)|Thomas Barnes]] (1747\u20131810) as divinity tutor in the Manchester academy.  Barnes, an evangelical Arian, gave him no encouragement, but he did not reject the offer till February 1798; it was accepted soon after by [[George Walker (Presbyterian)|George Walker]]. On Walker's resignation the trustees proposed (25 March 1803) to remove the institution to York if Wellbeloved would become its director.  He agreed (11 April), and from September 1803 to June 1840 the institution was known as Manchester College, York, which eventually became [[Harris Manchester College, Oxford]].  Its management was retained by a committee, meeting ordinarily in Manchester.  For thirty-seven years Wellbeloved discharged the duties of the divinity chair in a spirit described by [[James Martineau|Dr. James Martineau]], his pupil, as \"candid and catholic, simple and thorough\".  He followed the method which [[Richard Watson (bishop)|Richard Watson]] (1737\u20131816) had introduced at Cambridge, discarding systematic theology and substituting biblical exegesis.\n\nPresentations of plate (1840) and of 1,000''l'' (1843) were made to him on resigning his divinity chair.  He retained his connection with his chapel until his death, officiating occasionally until 1853, having as assistants John Wright (1845\u201346) and Henry Vaughan Palmer (1846\u201358).  He died at his residence, Monkgate, York, on 29 August 1858, and was buried (3 September) in the graveyard of St.Saviourgate Chapel; a memorial tablet is in the chapel.  His portrait, painted in 1826 by [[James Lonsdale (painter)|James Lonsdale]],<!--  was in the possession of G. W. Rayner Wood at Singleton Lodge, Manchester; copies are in the museum of the Yorkshire Philosophical Society and the vestry of St. Saviourgate Chapel; --> was engraved by [[Samuel Cousins]].<ref name=\"DNB00\" />\n\n===Antiquarian===\nWellbeloved was the Honorary Curator of Antiquities for the Yorkshire Philosophical Society from 1823 until his death in 1858, overseeing the exhibition and interpretation of antiquities in the [[Yorkshire Museum]] from its opening in 1830.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Philosophers and Provincials: The Yorkshire Philosophical Society from 1822 to 1844 |author1=Orange, A. D. |date= 1973 |publisher=Yorkshire Philosophical Society |page=23}</ref> Between 1827 and 1829 he oversaw excavations in the cloister of [[St Mary's Abbey, York]] preparatory to digging the Yorkshire Museum's foundation.<ref name= 'MedYork'>{{cite book |author1=Dean, G. |date=2008 |title=Medieval York |publisher=History Press |page=86}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\nProposals for editing a family bible were made to Wellbeloved (14 March 1814) by David Eaton (1771\u20131829), then a bookseller in Holborn in succession to [[William Vidler]]. The prospectus (May 1814) announced a revised translation with commentary. Between 1819 and 1838 nine parts were issued in large quarto, containing the Pentateuch, Job, Psalms, Proverbs, Ecclesiastes, and Canticles. The text was reprinted, with Wellbeloved's revised version of Joshua, Judges, Ruth, and the Minor Prophets, in \u2018The Holy Scriptures of the Old Covenant,\u2019 1859\u201362, 3 vols. 8vo. In 1823 he took up a controversy, begun by Thomas Thrush (1761\u20131843), with [[Francis Wrangham]] [[Sydney Smith]] wrote: \"If I had a cause to gain I would fee Mr. Wellbeloved to plead for me, and double fee Mr. Wrangham to plead against me.\" As a sub-trustee of the [[Sarah Hewley Trust]] he was involved in the suit (1830\u201342) which removed Unitarians from its management and benefits.\n\nHe was one of the founders of the York Subscription Library (1794), the [[Yorkshire Philosophical Society]] (1822), and the York Institute (1827), and devoted much time to the archaeology of [[York]]. His archaeological work included excavation in advance of the construction of the [https://web.archive.org/web/20131020154947/http://www.yorkshiremuseum.org.uk/Page/Index.aspx Yorkshire Museum and Gardens], the history of which is published in A Handbook to the Antiquities in the Grounds and Museum of the Yorkshire Philosophical Society.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wellbeloved|first=Charles|title=A Handbook to the Antiquities in the Grounds and Museum of the Yorkshire Philosophical Society|year=1881|publisher=J. Sampson|location=York|url=https://archive.org/details/handbooktoantiqu00wellrich}}</ref>  After the fire of 2 February 1829 he took a leading part in raising funds for the restoration of the minster, and in opposing the removal of the choir-screen. The description of the minster in Lewis's ''Topographical Dictionary,'' the article 'York' in the ''[[Penny Cyclop\u00e6dia]],'' and a ''Guide'' (1804) to York Minster are from his pen. His ''Eburacum, or York under the Romans'' (York, 1842, 8vo), gives the substance of his previous papers and lectures on the subject.<ref name=\"DNB00\" />\n\nBesides the works mentioned above, and single sermons and pamphlets, he published: \n* ''Devotional Exercises,'' 1801, 12mo; 8th edit. 1832.\n* ''Memoirs of \u2026 Rev. W[illiam] Wood,'' 1809, 8vo. Regarding the botanist, minister [[William Wood (botanist)|William Wood]]\n* ''Three Letters \u2026 to Francis Wrangham,'' 1823, 8vo; 2nd edit. same year.\n* ''Three Additional Letters,'' 1824, 8vo.\n* ''Memoir\u2019 prefixed to \u2018Sermons,'' 1826, 8vo, by Thomas Watson.\n* ''Account of \u2026 the Abbey of St. Mary, York,'' in ''[[Vetusta Monumenta]],'' 1829, vol. v. fol.\n* ''Memoir of Thomas Thrush,'' 1845, 8vo.\n* ''Descriptive Account of the Antiquities in the Museum of the Yorkshire Philosophical Society,'' 1852, 8vo; 3rd edit. 1858.\n\nHe contributed to the ''Yorkshire Repository,'' 1794, 12mo; the ''Annual Review,'' 1802\u20138; and the ''Proceedings of the Yorkshire Philosophical Society,'' 1855, vol. i.<ref name=DNB00>{{cite DNB|wstitle =Wellbeloved, Charles|first =Alexander|last = Gordon |authorlink =Alexander Gordon (Unitarian)|volume=60|quote=''sources:'' [Biographical Memoir by John Kenrick, 1860; Funeral Sermons by Thomas Hincks and William Gaskell, 1858; Christian Reformer, 1856 p. 229, 1858 pp. 617, 650, 683, 708, 1859 p. 19; Memoirs of Catherine Cappe, 1822, p. 255; Roll of Students, Manchester College, 1868; Kenrick's Memorials of St. Saviourgate, York, 1869, p. 52; unpublished letters of Wellbeloved and Kenrick; pedigree extracted from family bible by the Rev. C. H. Wellbeloved, Southport.]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{DNB|wstitle =Wellbeloved, Charles|volume=60}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wellbeloved, Charles}}\n[[Category:1769 births]]\n[[Category:1858 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Homerton College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British archaeologists]]\n[[Category:English Unitarians]]\n[[Category:Employees of the Yorkshire Museum]]\n[[Category:Members of the Yorkshire Philosophical Society]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the monarch known as Charles the Well-Beloved|Charles VI of France}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name = Charles Wellbeloved\n|image =YORAG 1202-PCF.jpg\n|caption=Portrait of Charles Wellbeloved\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1769|04|06|df=yes}}\n|birth_place = {{Nowrap|Denmark Street, [[St Giles]], [[London]], England}}\n|death_date = {{Death date and age|1858|08|29|1769|04|06|df=y}} \n|death_place = [[Monkgate]], [[York]], England\n|resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|nationality =\n|citizenship = \n|known_for = \n|alma_mater = \n|height =\n}}\n'''Charles Wellbeloved''' (6 April 1769 \u2013 29 August 1858) was an [[English people|English]] [[Christian Unitarianism|Unitarian]] [[Anglicanism#Anglican divines|divine]] and [[Archaeology|archaeologist]].\n\n==Biography==\nCharles Wellbeloved, only child of John Wellbeloved (1742\u20131787), by his wife Elizabeth Plaw, was born in Denmark Street, [[St Giles, London]], on 6 April 1769, and baptised on 25 April at [[St. Giles-in-the-Fields]]. Owing to domestic unhappiness he was brought up from the age of four by his grandfather, Charles Wellbeloved (1713\u20131782), a country gentleman at [[Mortlake]], Surrey, an Anglican, and the friend and follower of [[John Wesley]]. He got the best part of his early education from a clergyman named Delafosse at Richmond.  In 1783 he was placed with a firm of drapers on Holborn Hill, but only learned \"how to tie up a parcel\".\n\nIn 1785 he became a student at [[Homerton Academy]] under Benjamin Davies.  Among his fellow-students were [[William Field (Unitarian minister)|William Field]] and David Jones (1765\u20131816).  Jones was expelled for heresy in 1786; his opinions had influenced Wellbeloved, who was allowed to finish the session of 1787, but not to return.  In September 1787 he followed Jones to New College, Hackney, under [[Abraham Rees]], the cyclop\u00e6dist, and [[Andrew Kippis]], and subsequently (1789) under [[Thomas Belsham]] and (1790) [[Gilbert Wakefield]].  Here he formed a close friendship with [[Arthur Aikin]], who entered in 1789.  He attended the ministry of [[Richard Price]] (1723\u20131791).  \n\nHe married his wife Ann Kinder (d. 31 January 1823) on 1 July 1793, at St. Mary's, [[Stoke Newington]], with whom he had several children. Their youngest son, [[Robert Wellbeloved]] (15 July 1803&nbsp;\u2013 21 February 1856), married heiress Sarah Scott on 17 February 1830 and assumed the name and arms of Scott on her father's death in 1832.  Robert was a deputy-lieutenant for [[Worcestershire]] and M.P. for [[Walsall]] (1841\u201346).<ref name=\"DNB00\" /> His youngest daughter, Emma (d. 29 July 1842), married (1831) [[James Carter (judge)|Sir James Carter]], chief justice of New Brunswick.<ref name=\"MacNutt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.biographi.ca/009004-119.01-e.php?&id_nbr=4883|title=Carter, Sir James|last=MacNutt|first=William Stewart|work=Dictionary of Canadian Biography Online, vol. 10|publisher=University of Toronto|accessdate=29 November 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Ecclesiastical career===\nWellbeloved's first sermon was preached at [[Walthamstow]] on 13 November 1791.  Shortly afterwards he received through Michael Maurice, father of [John] [[Frederick Denison Maurice]], an invitation to become assistant to [[Newcome Cappe]] at [[York Unitarian Chapel|St Saviourgate Chapel]], [[York]].  He accepted on 23 January 1792, and began his duties at York on 5 February.  In 1801 he became sole minister on Cappe's death. The chief feature of his [[exegetical]] work was his treatment of prophecy, limiting the range of its prediction, confining that of Hebrew prophecy to the age of its production, and bounding our Lord's predictions by the destruction of Jerusalem. He broke with the Priestley school, rejecting a general resurrection and fixing the last judgment at death. In these and other points he closely followed the system of [[Newcome Cappe]], but his careful avoidance of dogmatism left his pupils free, and none of them followed him into \u2018Cappism.\u2019 Among his coadjutors were [[Theophilus Browne]], [[William Turner (biographer)|William Turner]]<ref>see [[William Turner (1714\u20131794)]]</ref> and William Hincks.<ref>[see under , [[Robert Dix Hincks]]]</ref> From 1810 he had the invaluable co-operation of [[John Kenrick (historian)|John Kenrick]], who married his elder daughter L\u00e6titia.\n\nIn 1794 he began to take pupils into a Sunday school he had founded. He was invited in November 1797 (after Belsham had declined) to succeed [[Thomas Barnes (Unitarian)|Thomas Barnes]] (1747\u20131810) as divinity tutor in the Manchester academy.  Barnes, an evangelical Arian, gave him no encouragement, but he did not reject the offer till February 1798; it was accepted soon after by [[George Walker (Presbyterian)|George Walker]]. On Walker's resignation the trustees proposed (25 March 1803) to remove the institution to York if Wellbeloved would become its director.  He agreed (11 April), and from September 1803 to June 1840 the institution was known as Manchester College, York, which eventually became [[Harris Manchester College, Oxford]].  Its management was retained by a committee, meeting ordinarily in Manchester.  For thirty-seven years Wellbeloved discharged the duties of the divinity chair in a spirit described by [[James Martineau|Dr. James Martineau]], his pupil, as \"candid and catholic, simple and thorough\".  He followed the method which [[Richard Watson (bishop)|Richard Watson]] (1737\u20131816) had introduced at Cambridge, discarding systematic theology and substituting biblical exegesis.\n\nPresentations of plate (1840) and of 1,000''l'' (1843) were made to him on resigning his divinity chair.  He retained his connection with his chapel until his death, officiating occasionally until 1853, having as assistants John Wright (1845\u201346) and Henry Vaughan Palmer (1846\u201358).  He died at his residence, Monkgate, York, on 29 August 1858, and was buried (3 September) in the graveyard of St.Saviourgate Chapel; a memorial tablet is in the chapel.  His portrait, painted in 1826 by [[James Lonsdale (painter)|James Lonsdale]],<!--  was in the possession of G. W. Rayner Wood at Singleton Lodge, Manchester; copies are in the museum of the Yorkshire Philosophical Society and the vestry of St. Saviourgate Chapel; --> was engraved by [[Samuel Cousins]].<ref name=\"DNB00\" />\n\n===Antiquarian===\nWellbeloved was the Honorary Curator of Antiquities for the Yorkshire Philosophical Society from 1823 until his death in 1858, overseeing the exhibition and interpretation of antiquities in the [[Yorkshire Museum]] from its opening in 1830.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Philosophers and Provincials: The Yorkshire Philosophical Society from 1822 to 1844 |author1=Orange, A. D. |date= 1973 |publisher=Yorkshire Philosophical Society |page=23}</ref> Between 1827 and 1829 he oversaw excavations in the cloister of [[St Mary's Abbey, York]] preparatory to digging the Yorkshire Museum's foundation.<ref name= 'MedYork'>{{cite book |author1=Dean, G. |date=2008 |title=Medieval York |publisher=History Press |page=86}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\nProposals for editing a family bible were made to Wellbeloved (14 March 1814) by David Eaton (1771\u20131829), then a bookseller in Holborn in succession to [[William Vidler]]. The prospectus (May 1814) announced a revised translation with commentary. Between 1819 and 1838 nine parts were issued in large quarto, containing the Pentateuch, Job, Psalms, Proverbs, Ecclesiastes, and Canticles. The text was reprinted, with Wellbeloved's revised version of Joshua, Judges, Ruth, and the Minor Prophets, in \u2018The Holy Scriptures of the Old Covenant,\u2019 1859\u201362, 3 vols. 8vo. In 1823 he took up a controversy, begun by Thomas Thrush (1761\u20131843), with [[Francis Wrangham]] [[Sydney Smith]] wrote: \"If I had a cause to gain I would fee Mr. Wellbeloved to plead for me, and double fee Mr. Wrangham to plead against me.\" As a sub-trustee of the [[Sarah Hewley Trust]] he was involved in the suit (1830\u201342) which removed Unitarians from its management and benefits.\n\nHe was one of the founders of the York Subscription Library (1794), the [[Yorkshire Philosophical Society]] (1822), and the York Institute (1827), and devoted much time to the archaeology of [[York]]. His archaeological work included excavation in advance of the construction of the [https://web.archive.org/web/20131020154947/http://www.yorkshiremuseum.org.uk/Page/Index.aspx Yorkshire Museum and Gardens], the history of which is published in A Handbook to the Antiquties in the Grounds and Museum of the Yorkshire Philosophical Society.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wellbeloved|first=Charles|title=A Handbook to the Antiquities in the Grounds and Museum of the Yorkshire Philosophical Society|year=1881|publisher=J. Sampson|location=York|url=https://archive.org/details/handbooktoantiqu00wellrich}}</ref>  After the fire of 2 February 1829 he took a leading part in raising funds for the restoration of the minster, and in opposing the removal of the choir-screen. The description of the minster in Lewis's ''Topographical Dictionary,'' the article 'York' in the ''[[Penny Cyclop\u00e6dia]],'' and a ''Guide'' (1804) to York Minster are from his pen. His ''Eburacum, or York under the Romans'' (York, 1842, 8vo), gives the substance of his previous papers and lectures on the subject.<ref name=\"DNB00\" />\n\nBesides the works mentioned above, and single sermons and pamphlets, he published: \n* ''Devotional Exercises,'' 1801, 12mo; 8th edit. 1832.\n* ''Memoirs of \u2026 Rev. W[illiam] Wood,'' 1809, 8vo. Regarding the botanist, minister [[William Wood (botanist)|William Wood]]\n* ''Three Letters \u2026 to Francis Wrangham,'' 1823, 8vo; 2nd edit. same year.\n* ''Three Additional Letters,'' 1824, 8vo.\n* ''Memoir\u2019 prefixed to \u2018Sermons,'' 1826, 8vo, by Thomas Watson.\n* ''Account of \u2026 the Abbey of St. Mary, York,'' in ''[[Vetusta Monumenta]],'' 1829, vol. v. fol.\n* ''Memoir of Thomas Thrush,'' 1845, 8vo.\n* ''Descriptive Account of the Antiquities in the Museum of the Yorkshire Philosophical Society,'' 1852, 8vo; 3rd edit. 1858.\n\nHe contributed to the ''Yorkshire Repository,'' 1794, 12mo; the ''Annual Review,'' 1802\u20138; and the ''Proceedings of the Yorkshire Philosophical Society,'' 1855, vol. i.<ref name=DNB00>{{cite DNB|wstitle =Wellbeloved, Charles|first =Alexander|last = Gordon |authorlink =Alexander Gordon (Unitarian)|volume=60|quote=''sources:'' [Biographical Memoir by John Kenrick, 1860; Funeral Sermons by Thomas Hincks and William Gaskell, 1858; Christian Reformer, 1856 p. 229, 1858 pp. 617, 650, 683, 708, 1859 p. 19; Memoirs of Catherine Cappe, 1822, p. 255; Roll of Students, Manchester College, 1868; Kenrick's Memorials of St. Saviourgate, York, 1869, p. 52; unpublished letters of Wellbeloved and Kenrick; pedigree extracted from family bible by the Rev. C. H. Wellbeloved, Southport.]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{DNB|wstitle =Wellbeloved, Charles|volume=60}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wellbeloved, Charles}}\n[[Category:1769 births]]\n[[Category:1858 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Homerton College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British archaeologists]]\n[[Category:English Unitarians]]\n[[Category:Employees of the Yorkshire Museum]]\n[[Category:Members of the Yorkshire Philosophical Society]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "Antiquties->Antiquities -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Wellbeloved"}
{"title_page": "Sicilian Buttercup", "text_new": "{{infobox poultry breed\n| name          = Sicilian Buttercup\n| image         = Buttercup Chicken1.jpg\n| image_size    =\n| alt           = \n| image_caption =A Sicilian Buttercup hen\n| status        = [[Livestock Conservancy]]: threatened{{r|albc}}\n| altname       =\n| country       =  [[Sicily]], Italy\n| distribution  =\n| standard      =\n| use           = \n| nickname      =\n| apa           = Mediterranean{{r|apa}}\n| aba           = \n| ee            = \n| pcgb          =Rare soft feather: light{{r|pcgb}}\n| maleweight    = 2.95 kg\n| femaleweight  = 2.50 kg\n| skincolor     = \n| eggcolor      = \n| comb          = Buttercup comb\n| note          = \n| type          = [[Chicken]]\n| latin         = Gallus gallus domesticus\n}}\n\nThe '''Sicilian Buttercup''' is a [[List of chicken breeds|breed]] of domestic [[chicken]] originating from the island of [[Sicily]]. The breed was imported to the United States in the 19th century, and to Britain and Australia early in the 20th century. It derives from the indigenous [[Siciliana chicken|Siciliana]] breed of Sicily, but long separation from the original stock has led to marked differences between the two.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Gallus turcicus.jpg|thumb|''Gallus turcicus'', from the ''Ornithologiae tomus alter'' of [[Ulisse Aldrovandi]] (1522\u20131605)]]\nThe Siciliana breed of Sicily appears to derive from ancient inter-breeding of local birds with North African stock{{r|dad}} such as the rose-combed Berbera breed{{r|trecc|trecc2|page=701}} or the Tripolitana described by Tucci.{{r|tucci}} These birds may have been similar to the \"Gallus turcicus\" described by [[Ulisse Aldrovandi]] in 1600.{{r|aldro|mersch}} Similar chickens are depicted in 16th-century paintings in the [[Vatican Museums]] and the [[Galleria Borghese]] in [[Rome]], and in [[Florence]] and [[Paris]].{{r|zanon|trib}}\n\nIn about 1863{{r|bureau|page=439}} or 1877,{{r|gent|page=22}} a certain Cephas Dawes of [[Dedham, Massachusetts]], captain of the ''Frutiere'', was loading oranges in Sicily and bought a number of chickens to provide meat on his homeward journey. Some of these continued to lay well during the voyage, and were kept for eggs instead. Some of them were later sold to his neighbor, C. Carroll Loring, also of Dedham, who became their first breeder.  Loring named the Sicilian Buttercup and he promoted them as prolific layers until at least 1905.{{r|bureau|gent|page=439|page2=22}} There are claims that all current American Buttercups descend from a shipment of hatchlings in 1892.{{r|albc}} \n\nA breeders' association, the American Buttercup Club, was formed the United States in 1912, and by 1914 had 600 members; a similar association formed in Britain in 1913.{{r|butler}} The Sicilian Buttercup was included in the [[Standard of Perfection]] of the [[American Poultry Association]] in 1918.{{r|apa}} It is listed as \"threatened\" by the American [[Livestock Conservancy]]{{r|albc}} and is on the \"Rare and Native Breeds\" list of the British [[Rare Breeds Survival Trust]].{{r|rbst}} \n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist|45em|refs=\n\n<ref name=albc>[http://www.livestockconservancy.org/index.php/heritage/internal/buttercup Buttercup Chicken] The Livestock Conservancy. Accessed June 2015.</ref>\n\n<ref name=aldro>Aldrovandi, Ulisse (1600) [http://amshistorica.unibo.it/33 ''Ornithologiae tomus alter...cum indice copiosissimo variarum linguarum''] (in Latin) Bononiae: apud Io. Bapt. Bellagamba. pp.314\u2013316.</ref>\n\n<ref name=apa>[https://web.archive.org/web/20131101222318/http://www.amerpoultryassn.com/PDF%20Forms/APA%20Recognized%20Breeds%20and%20Varieties%20Sept2012.pdf APA Recognized Breeds and Varieties as of January 1, 2012]. American Poultry Association. Archived 1 November 2013.</ref>\n\n<ref name=bureau>United States Bureau of Animal Industry (1905) [https://books.google.com/books?id=zYLwAAAAMAAJ Twenty-first annual report of the Bureau of Animal Industry for the year 1904] Washington, DC: Government Printing Office.</ref>\n\n<ref name=butler>E. van Benthuysen (11 June 1914). [https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4111682/american_buttercup_club_1912_600/ Buttercups \u2013 Most Recent Chicken Breed]. ''Butler County Democrat'' (Hamilton, Ohio). {{nobreak|p. 6.}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=dad>Breed data sheet: Siciliana/Italy in [http://dad.fao.org/ Domestic Animal Diversity Information System] Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations. Accessed January 2012.</ref>\n\n<ref name=gent>[s.n.] (1910) [https://books.google.com/books?id=Fw4iAQAAMAAJ Is the Buttercup a daisy?] ''The Country Gentleman'', Volume 75. Albany, NY: Luther Tucker & Son.</ref>\n\n<ref name=mersch>Mersch, Nuele [http://www.sizilianer.info/pages/e-siciliana.html Crowned heads and green feet: Siciliana] Erhaltungszuchtverein f\u00fcr sizilianische H\u00fchnerrassen. Accessed January 2012</ref>\n\n<ref name=pcgb>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143235/http://www.poultryclub.org/img/Breed%20Classification.pdf Breed Classification]. Poultry Club of Great Britain. Archived 12 June 2018.</ref>\n\n<ref name=rbst>[https://www.rbst.org.uk/Rare-and-Native-Breeds/Poultry/Chickens/(offset)/20 Rare and Native Breeds: Chickens]. Rare Breeds Survival Trust. Accessed June 2015.</ref>\n\n<ref name=trecc>Gentile, Giovanni; Calogero Tumminelli (eds.) (1929-39) [https://books.google.com/books?id=EFgPAQAAMAAJ ''Enciclopedia italiana di scienze, lettere ed arti'', Vol. 27]. (in Italian) [Roma]: Istituto Giovanni Treccani. \"Italian encyclopaedia of science, literature and the arts\".</ref>\n\n<ref name=trecc2>[http://www.treccani.it/vocabolario/berbero1/ Razza berbera (b)] (in Italian) Treccani Vocabolario online. Accessed January 2012.</ref>\n\n<ref name=trib>[s.n.] (1925) [https://books.google.com/books?id=ZRBIAAAAYAAJ Sicilian Buttercup] ''Poultry tribune'', Volume 31. Poultry-Dairy Pub. Co. p.50.</ref>\n\n<ref name=tucci>Tucci, Prof. Francesco (1931) ''Gli allevamenti del bestiame in Tripolitania'' (in Italian) Roma: Sindacato italiano arti grafiche. pp.201\u2013205. \"Stock-raising in Tripolitania\".</ref>\n\n<ref name=zanon>Zanon, Alessio [http://www.ilpollaiodelre.com/polliIt4.htm Siciliana] (in Italian) Il Pollaio del Re. Accessed January 2012. \"The Siciliana\"</ref>\n\n}}\n{{Commonscat inline}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sicilian Buttercup (Chicken)}}\n[[Category:Conservation Priority Breeds of the Livestock Conservancy]]\n[[Category:Chicken breeds]]\n[[Category:Chicken breeds originating in Italy]]\n[[Category:Chicken breeds originating in Sicily]]\n[[Category:Animal breeds on the RBST Watchlist]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox poultry breed\n| name          = Sicilian Buttercup\n| image         = Buttercup Chicken1.jpg\n| image_size    =\n| alt           = \n| image_caption =A Sicilian Buttercup hen\n| status        = [[Livestock Conservancy]]: threatened{{r|albc}}\n| altname       =\n| country       =  [[Sicily]], Italy\n| distribution  =\n| standard      =\n| use           = \n| nickname      =\n| apa           = Mediterranean{{r|apa}}\n| aba           = \n| ee            = \n| pcgb          =Rare soft feather: light{{r|pcgb}}\n| maleweight    = 2.95 kg\n| femaleweight  = 2.50 kg\n| skincolor     = \n| eggcolor      = \n| comb          = Buttercup comb\n| note          = \n| type          = [[Chicken]]\n| latin         = Gallus gallus domesticus\n}}\n\nThe '''Sicilian Buttercup''' is a [[List of chicken breeds|breed]] of domestic [[chicken]] originating from the island of [[Sicily]]. The breed was imported to the United States in the 19th century, and to Britain and Australia early in the 20th century. It derives from the indigenous [[Siciliana chicken|Siciliana]] breed of Sicily, but long separation from the original stock has led to marked differences between the two.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Gallus turcicus.jpg|thumb|''Gallus turcicus'', from the ''Ornithologiae tomus alter'' of [[Ulisse Aldrovandi]] (1522\u20131605)]]\nThe Siciliana breed of Sicily appears to derive from ancient inter-breeding of local birds with North African stock{{r|dad}} such as the rose-combed Berbera breed{{r|trecc|trecc2|page=701}} or the Tripolitana described by Tucci.{{r|tucci}} These birds may have been similar to the \"Gallus turcicus\" described by [[Ulisse Aldrovandi]] in 1600.{{r|aldro|mersch}} Similar chickens are depicted in 16th-century paintings in the [[Vatican Museums]] and the [[Galleria Borghese]] in [[Rome]], and in [[Florence]] and [[Paris]].{{r|zanon|trib}}\n\nIn about 1863{{r|bureau|page=439}} or 1877,{{r|gent|page=22}} a certain Cephas Dawes of [[Dedham, Massachusetts]], captain of the ''Frutiere'', was loading oranges in Sicily and bought a number of chickens to provide meat on his homeward journey. Some of these continued to lay well during the voyage, and were kept for eggs instead. Some of them were later sold to one C. Carroll Loring, also of Dedham, who became the first breeder of what would become the Sicilian Buttercup.{{r|bureau|gent|page=439|page2=22}} All American Buttercups, however, descend from a later shipment of hatchlings, in 1892.{{r|albc}} \n\nA breeders' association, the American Buttercup Club, was formed the United States in 1912, and by 1914 had 600 members; a similar association formed in Britain in 1913.{{r|butler}} The Sicilian Buttercup was included in the [[Standard of Perfection]] of the [[American Poultry Association]] in 1918.{{r|apa}} It is listed as \"threatened\" by the American [[Livestock Conservancy]]{{r|albc}} and is on the \"Rare and Native Breeds\" list of the British [[Rare Breeds Survival Trust]].{{r|rbst}} \n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist|45em|refs=\n\n<ref name=albc>[http://www.livestockconservancy.org/index.php/heritage/internal/buttercup Buttercup Chicken] The Livestock Conservancy. Accessed June 2015.</ref>\n\n<ref name=aldro>Aldrovandi, Ulisse (1600) [http://amshistorica.unibo.it/33 ''Ornithologiae tomus alter...cum indice copiosissimo variarum linguarum''] (in Latin) Bononiae: apud Io. Bapt. Bellagamba. pp.314\u2013316.</ref>\n\n<ref name=apa>[https://web.archive.org/web/20131101222318/http://www.amerpoultryassn.com/PDF%20Forms/APA%20Recognized%20Breeds%20and%20Varieties%20Sept2012.pdf APA Recognized Breeds and Varieties as of January 1, 2012]. American Poultry Association. Archived 1 November 2013.</ref>\n\n<ref name=bureau>United States Bureau of Animal Industry (1905) [https://books.google.com/books?id=zYLwAAAAMAAJ Twenty-first annual report of the Bureau of Animal Industry for the year 1904] Washington, DC: Government Printing Office.</ref>\n\n<ref name=butler>E. van Benthuysen (11 June 1914). [https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4111682/american_buttercup_club_1912_600/ Buttercups \u2013 Most Recent Chicken Breed]. ''Butler County Democrat'' (Hamilton, Ohio). {{nobreak|p. 6.}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=dad>Breed data sheet: Siciliana/Italy in [http://dad.fao.org/ Domestic Animal Diversity Information System] Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations. Accessed January 2012.</ref>\n\n<ref name=gent>[s.n.] (1910) [https://books.google.com/books?id=Fw4iAQAAMAAJ Is the Buttercup a daisy?] ''The Country Gentleman'', Volume 75. Albany, NY: Luther Tucker & Son.</ref>\n\n<ref name=mersch>Mersch, Nuele [http://www.sizilianer.info/pages/e-siciliana.html Crowned heads and green feet: Siciliana] Erhaltungszuchtverein f\u00fcr sizilianische H\u00fchnerrassen. Accessed January 2012</ref>\n\n<ref name=pcgb>[https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143235/http://www.poultryclub.org/img/Breed%20Classification.pdf Breed Classification]. Poultry Club of Great Britain. Archived 12 June 2018.</ref>\n\n<ref name=rbst>[https://www.rbst.org.uk/Rare-and-Native-Breeds/Poultry/Chickens/(offset)/20 Rare and Native Breeds: Chickens]. Rare Breeds Survival Trust. Accessed June 2015.</ref>\n\n<ref name=trecc>Gentile, Giovanni; Calogero Tumminelli (eds.) (1929-39) [https://books.google.com/books?id=EFgPAQAAMAAJ ''Enciclopedia italiana di scienze, lettere ed arti'', Vol. 27]. (in Italian) [Roma]: Istituto Giovanni Treccani. \"Italian encyclopaedia of science, literature and the arts\".</ref>\n\n<ref name=trecc2>[http://www.treccani.it/vocabolario/berbero1/ Razza berbera (b)] (in Italian) Treccani Vocabolario online. Accessed January 2012.</ref>\n\n<ref name=trib>[s.n.] (1925) [https://books.google.com/books?id=ZRBIAAAAYAAJ Sicilian Buttercup] ''Poultry tribune'', Volume 31. Poultry-Dairy Pub. Co. p.50.</ref>\n\n<ref name=tucci>Tucci, Prof. Francesco (1931) ''Gli allevamenti del bestiame in Tripolitania'' (in Italian) Roma: Sindacato italiano arti grafiche. pp.201\u2013205. \"Stock-raising in Tripolitania\".</ref>\n\n<ref name=zanon>Zanon, Alessio [http://www.ilpollaiodelre.com/polliIt4.htm Siciliana] (in Italian) Il Pollaio del Re. Accessed January 2012. \"The Siciliana\"</ref>\n\n}}\n{{Commonscat inline}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sicilian Buttercup (Chicken)}}\n[[Category:Conservation Priority Breeds of the Livestock Conservancy]]\n[[Category:Chicken breeds]]\n[[Category:Chicken breeds originating in Italy]]\n[[Category:Chicken breeds originating in Sicily]]\n[[Category:Animal breeds on the RBST Watchlist]]\n", "name_user": "Johnkoger", "label": "safe", "comment": "I read the source material, {{r|bureau|gent|page=439|page2+22}} and gave Loring slightly more credit than the previous Wikipedia version gave to him.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sicilian_Buttercup"}
{"title_page": "Basim al-Karbalaei", "text_new": "[[Hajji|Haj]] [[Mullah|Mulla]] '''Basim Ismail Muhammad-Ali al-Karbalaei''' ({{Lang-ar|\u0628\u0627\u0633\u0645 \u0625\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0639\u064a\u0644 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0639\u0644\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0631\u0628\u0644\u0627\u0626\u064a}}; born November 11, 1966), commonly known as '''Basim Al-Karbalai''' or '''Basim Karbalaei''' or '''Mulla Basim''' is a [[Shia]] [[Mourning of Muharram|eulogy]] [[Mourner|reciter]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lou\u00ebr|first=Laurence|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=B8wnEtH8oDgC&printsec=frontcover&dq=basim+karbalai&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjn5tbHi7foAhXSoVwKHcT3AucQ6AEIMDAB|title=Transnational Shia Politics: Religious and Political Networks in the Gulf|date=2011|publisher=Hurst|year=|isbn=978-1-84904-214-7|location=|pages=216|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Ghazoul|first=Ferial J.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=_qY8vzSVwwMC&pg=PA16&dq=%22Basim+Al-Karbalaei%22&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22Basim%20Al-Karbalaei%22&f=false|title=al-Iqtibas al-Fani: Muqaranat Tatbiqiya Wa Mafahim Nadhariya|date=2008|publisher=American Univ in Cairo Press|year=|isbn=978-977-416-195-7|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=Artistic Adaptaions: Approaches and Positions}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=GYwjAQAAIAAJ&q=basim+karbalai&dq=basim+karbalai&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiivL3PjrfoAhW-QEEAHe5oCXcQ6AEIKDAA|title=Abstracts of the Annual Meeting|date=2008|publisher=American Anthropological Association.|year=|isbn=|volume=107|location=|pages=603|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Mervin|first=Sabrina|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ga0NAQAAQBAJ|title=The Dynamics of Sunni-Shia Relationships: Doctrine, Transnationalism, Intellectuals and the Media|last2=Brunner|first2=Rainer|last3=Legrain|first3=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois|last4=Alagha|first4=Joseph|last5=Visser|first5=Reidar|last6=Pierret|first6=Thomas|last7=Meijer|first7=Roel|last8=Wagemakers|first8=Joas|last9=Dudoignon|first9=St\u00e9phane A.|date=2013-05-29|publisher=Hurst Publishers|year=|isbn=978-1-84904-217-8|location=|pages=110|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/12/iraq-religious-shiite-chants-revival.html|title=Return of once forbidden Ashoura chants signals Shiite revival|last=Zeed|first=Adnan Abu|date=2013-12-17|website=Al-Monitor|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mozn.net/?act=artc&id=1669|title=Basim al-Karbalaei Anmuthajan Lil Madrasah al-Fashila|last=Al Mubarak|first=Wajdi|date=2008-04-21|website=Mozon Cultural Network|language=ar|trans-title=Basim Karbalaei, An Example of a Failed School|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\":42\">{{Cite news|last=Shamto|first=Samir|url=|title=Mulla Basim Awwal Hadith Sahafi Ba'd al-Ghurba|date=2003-08-01|work=al-Fajr Magazine|access-date=|url-status=live|language=ar|trans-title=Mulla Basim's First Journalistic Interview After Estrangement}}</ref><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=al-Tahdith Alal Kasida al-Husayniya|date=2010-02-01|work=Sada al-Rawdhatain Magazine|access-date=|url-status=live|language=ar|trans-title=Renewing the Husayni Elegy}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Abd al-Hurr|first=Munthir|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=_VPjCgAAQBAJ|title=Tuqus al-Ithm: Min Waqae' Ayam al-Mihna Fi Baghdad|date=2012-01-01|publisher=Al Manhal|year=|isbn=9796500123721|location=|pages=55|language=ar|trans-title=Rituals Of Sin: A Reality From the Days of Hardship in Baghdad}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MwUXAQAAIAAJ|title=al-Ra\u02bcy al-Akhar|date=1999|publisher=Markaz al-Tathq\u012bf al-Isl\u0101m\u012b|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar}}</ref>{{Infobox musical artist|\n| occupation       = Eulogy reciter\n| past_members     = \n| current_members  = \n| website          = http://bk-media.net/\n| associated_acts  = \n| label            = {{hlist|BK Media|al-Thaqalayn Records|al-Hayat Media|Fadak Records|Karbala Records|Anwar al-Huda|al-Raya al-Imamiya|\u0650Aniss al-Nofoss}}\n| Marriages        = \n| years_active     = 1981\u2013present\n| genre            = \n| name             = Basim al-Karbalaei\n| instrument       = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1966|11|11}}\n| birth_name       = Basim Ismail Muhammad-Ali\n| native_name      = \u0628\u0627\u0633\u0645 \u0625\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0639\u064a\u0644 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0639\u0644\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0631\u0628\u0644\u0627\u0626\u064a\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image_size       = \n| image            = Bassim Al-Karbalaei .jpg\n| birth_place      = [[Karbala]], [[Iraqi Republic (1958\u201368)|Iraq]]\n}}\nal-Karbalaei's voice and performance is considered particularly distinctive, the former is considered one of the most compelling instruments in the history of lamentations for the Ahl al-Bayt. His vocal abilities have allowed him to be identified as one of the greatest voices in the [[Arabs|Arab]] world, widely heard by audiences all across the globe.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Salah|first=Salah|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=CSCQBQAAQBAJ|title=Kayfa Taqtul al-Arnab|publisher=Moment Kutub Raqmiya|year=2014|isbn=|location=London, UK|pages=152, 167|language=ar|trans-title=How To Kill The Rabbit}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Antoon|first=Sinan|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Kx0QXCSEwuYC|title=The Corpse Washer|date=2013-07-30|publisher=Yale University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-300-19060-1|location=|pages=167|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Inan|first=Fadhil|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=bWPYAAAAMAAJ&q=%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%85+%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%83%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%A6%D9%8A&dq=%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B3%D9%85+%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%83%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%A6%D9%8A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiU1_bXsrfoAhVHXhUIHcWLC3kQ6AEIZDAG|title=Kitab Ashura: I\u1e63d\u0101r Sanaw\u012b Ya\u1e0dummu Fa\u02bb\u0101l\u012by\u0101t \u02bb\u0100sh\u016br\u0101\u02be al-Ba\u1e25rayn, 2003 M/1424 H|date=2003|publisher=Dar al-Neda|year=|isbn=|location=Bahrain|pages=473|language=ar}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.almodon.com/media/2016/10/4/\u0628\u0627\u0633\u0645-\u0627\u0644\u0643\u0631\u0628\u0644\u0627\u0626\u064a-\u0635\u0627\u0646\u0639-\u0627\u0644\u0625\u062d\u062a\u0632\u0627\u0646-\u0648\u0645\u062d\u062a\u0643\u0631\u0647|title=Basim Karbalaei: Sani' al-Ihtizan Wa Muhtakira|last=Outa|first=Rojiyah|date=|website=Al Modon E-Newspaper|language=ar|trans-title=Basim Karbalaei: Creator of Grief and it's Monopolizer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Abdallah|first=Tayseer|url=|title=Basim.. Madah al-Rasool|date=2005-05-07|work=Zahrat al-Khaleej|access-date=|url-status=live|language=ar|trans-title=Basim.. Praiser of the Messenger}}</ref>\n\nHis choice of poetry, melodies, performances, were able to attract millions of listeners, allowing them to abandon the types of music that are religiously forbidden. al-Karbalaei managed to fill a void for them, by continuously introducing new methods and styles in his recitations. He has also produced works languages other than Arabic, like [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Urdu]] and [[English language|English]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=al-Kaabi|first=Ahmed|title=Basim al-Karbalai Safir al-Inshad al-Husayni|publisher=Maktabat Tareeq al-Ma'rifa|year=2010|isbn=|location=Cairo, Egypt|pages=42|trans-title=Basim Karbalaei: The Ambassador of Husayni Eulogies}}</ref> al-Karbalaei, for the most of it, has been apolitical with his elegies, trying to keep his elegies exclusively about the Ahl al-Bayt and their memory.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://wesamalsebea.wordpress.com/%d8%ad%d9%88%d8%b1%d8%a7%d8%aa/%d8%a8%d8%a7%d8%b3%d9%85-%d8%a7%d9%84%d9%83%d8%b1%d8%a8%d9%84%d8%a7%d8%a6%d9%8a-%d8%a3%d9%8a%d9%82%d9%88%d9%86%d8%a9-%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%ad%d8%b2%d9%86-%d8%a7%d9%84%d9%85%d9%82%d9%8a%d9%85/|title=Basim al-Karbalaei: Iqonat al-Hizn al-Muqim|last=al-Sebea|first=Wesam|date=2012-06-21|website=Dr. Wesam al-Sabea's Blog|language=ar|trans-title=Basim Karbalaei: Icon Of Residing Grief|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, al-Karbalaei was gifted with a crown made of pure gold, and dubbed ''Sultan al-Minbar al-Hussaini'' (sultan of the Husayni pulpit), by the Hussaini Reciters Association in [[Kadhimiya]]. He later donated the crown to the [[Al Abbas Mosque|Abbas shrine]] museum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://alkafeel.net/news/index?id=7880&lang=en|title=Haj Basem al-Karbala'i donated the golden crown to the museum of the al-Abbas's (p) holy shrine.|last=Network|first=AlKafeel Global|website=alkafeel.net|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nal-Karbalaei was born in [[Karbala]], to Ismail al-Karbalaei, and Siddiqa al-Tukmachi. He is the fourth of seven children.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Kaabi|first=Ahmed|title=Basim al-Karbalai Safir al-Inshad al-Husayni|publisher=Maktabat Tareeq al-Ma'rifa|year=2010|isbn=|location=Cairo, Egypt|pages=35|trans-title=Basim Karbalaei: The Ambassador of Husayni Eulogies}}</ref> Whilst in Karbala, he was inspired by senior eulogy reciter [[Hamza al-Zighayir]], and participated in his ''majalis'' (plu. mourning gatherings), until he passed away in 1976.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ooUQAQAAIAAJ|title=al-Mawroothat Wa al-Shaaer Fi Karbala|date=2003|publisher=Dar al-Mahaja al-Baydha|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=169|language=ar|trans-title=The Inherited and the Rituals In Karbala}}</ref>\n\nIn 1980, al-Karbalaei and his family emigrated to [[Iran]], fleeing [[Ba'athist Iraq|Bathist]] persecution. He lived in [[Isfahan]], near his mother's family, and it was his uncle Rasool al-Tukmachi, who discovered al-Karbalaei's talent and began to encourage him to recite praises and lamentations in memory of the [[Ahl al-Bayt]].<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=al-Karbassi|first=Muhammad-Sadiq|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=f9OPDwAAQBAJ|title=Diwan al-Takhmis|date=2017-12-01|publisher=Hussaini Centre for Research|year=|isbn=978-1-78403-025-4|volume=3|location=London, UK|pages=53|language=ar|trans-title=Collection of Stanzas}}</ref> He was then taken under the wing of a Mulla Taq, who began taking him to the [[Hussainiya|Husayniya]]; established by the people of Karbala who resided in Isfahan, to participate in. The first ever eulogy he recited was ''Taj al-Sa'ada Lel Yiwali Haidar'' ({{Lang-ar|\u062a\u0627\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0639\u0627\u062f\u0629 \u0644\u0644\u064a\u0648\u0627\u0644\u064a \u062d\u064a\u062f\u0631}}), by renowned late poet, [[Kadhim Manthoor al-Karbalaei|Kadhim Manthoor]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Kaabi|first=Ahmed|title=Basim al-Karbalai Safir al-Inshad al-Husayni|publisher=Maktabat Tareeq al-Ma'rifa|year=2010|isbn=|location=Cairo, Egypt|pages=36-7|trans-title=Basim Karbalaei: The Ambassador of Husayni Eulogies}}</ref>\n\nal-Karbalaei, then began to recite in different cities across Iran, at Husayniya's established by the [[Iraqis in Iran|Iraqi community]]. His name quickly spread between the congregations, and began to attract the youth to his majalis, and through listening to him, they would cultivate pious sensibilities.<ref>{{Cite thesis|title=Following Sayyida Zaynab: Twelver Shi\u2018ism in Contemporary Syria|url=https://tspace.library.utoronto.ca/handle/1807/34935|date=2013-01-07|degree=|language=en-ca|first=Edith|last=Szanto|publisher=|doi=}}</ref>\n\nal-Karbalaei began reciting eulogies mainly written by Muhammad-Ridha Fatthallah. However, after the death of Fatthallah, he was introduced to Jaber al-Kadhimi. al-Karbalaei and al-Kadhimi got on very well, and whilst the former was considered to be a talented reciter, the latter was considered one of the best poets of that time. It was here that a long relationship began, where they would produce modern melodies and lyrics, straying away from the traditional tunes and poetry that were recited before them.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Kaabi|first=Ahmed|title=Basim al-Karbalai Safir al-Inshad al-Husayni|publisher=Maktabat Tareeq al-Ma'rifa|year=2010|isbn=|location=Cairo, Egypt|pages=38-9|trans-title=Basim Karbalaei: The Ambassador of Husayni Eulogies}}</ref>\n\nThe first ten nights of [[Muharram]] (that are spent retelling the story of the murder of [[Husayn ibn Ali|Hussain]], his family and his companions on [[Ashura]]) are considered second only to [[Ramadan]] in its significance, and its considered the largest in congregation compared to other mourning seasons, and every Shia eulogy reciter dreams of hosting these ten nights, and al-Karbalaei's first ten night function was in 1988, in Qom. That year witnessed the beginning of al-Karbalaei's recognition as a capable reciter.<ref>{{Cite book|last=el-Aswad|first=El-Sayed|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=CnzhXfJfkAMC|title=Muslim Worldviews and Everyday Lives|date=2012-07-13|publisher=Rowman Altamira|year=|isbn=978-0-7591-2119-5|location=|pages=67-8|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 1994, al-Karbalaei was invited to recite for the first ten nights of Muharram in [[Bneid Al-Gar|Kuwait]]. His majalis were recorded onto [[Cassette tape|tape cassettes]] and distributed across the Islamic world. This allowed exposure on a much larger scale, and gained him international recognition. He also began to receive invitations in other countries, as close as [[Lebanon]] and as far as [[Australia]]. He took residence in Kuwait, moving with his family.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Kaabi|first=Ahmed|title=Basim al-Karbalai Safir al-Inshad al-Husayni|publisher=Maktabat Tareeq al-Ma'rifa|year=2010|isbn=|location=Cairo, Egypt|pages=40-1|trans-title=Basim Karbalaei: The Ambassador of Husayni Eulogies}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the advise of his mentor, [[Mohammed Ridha al-Shirazi|Muhammad Ridha al-Shirazi]], he formed a group of aspiring reciters, called ''Shabab al-Thaqalayn'', which was an ensemble of eighty youth, similar to a choir. This group often participated in auspicious functions celebrating the births of the Ahl al-Bayt. The group produced a notable amount of senior reciters.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=Abbas|first=Salah|url=|title=Min al-Zinzana Ila al-Minbar|date=2001|work=al-Minbar Magazine|access-date=|url-status=live|language=ar|trans-title=From the Cell to the Pulpit}}</ref>\n\nUpon many invitations, al-Karbalaei's visited Bahrain for the first time in 2002, for the first ten nights of Muharram. This was also the first time al-Karbalaei he was going to leave Kuwait in Muharram, after performing there for eight consecutive years. This proved a new challenge for al-Karbalaei, since the people of Bahrain had a slightly different approach when it came to the culture of ''latom'' (chest beating). He managed to quickly cope and accommodate to their [[Metre (poetry)|metre]], earning the recognition as a true innovator in the eulogy reciter's world. \n\nAfter the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|invasion of Iraq]] in 2003, al-Karbalaei visited Iraq, after being separated from his homeland for just over twenty-three years. He was welcomed greatly by his fellow countrymen. Majalis were hosted for him, in each of the holy sites, with crowds reaching up to hundreds of thousands. However, al-Karbalaei did not remain in Iraq for too long and returned to Kuwait, whilst still focusing on his performances across the globe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OTVnRKfSe6I|title=Awdat al-Haj Basim al-Karbalai Ila al-Kadhimiya Ba'd Ghiyab 23 Sana|last=|first=|date=2003-07-26|website=YouTube|language=ar|trans-title=Return of Haj Basim Karbalaei To Kadhimiya After An Absence of 23 Years|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|quote=Basim first appears in the middle of the crowds in 01:45:00}}</ref> He spent the next couple of years of between [[Manama]] and [[London]] for Muharram, and other Arab and Western countries for the other seasons. Eventually in 2007, he left Kuwait altogether, to settle in his wife's hometown, in [[Oman]].<ref name=\":9\" />\n\n== Media ==\nal-Karbalaei is the first Shia eulogy reciter to produce a ''kasida'' ([[elegy]]) in a studio. His first production was a feature in a project with Dawood Hussein<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyfa.edu/film-school-blog/kuwaiti-actor-dawood-hussain-visits-nyfa-abu-dhabi/|title=Kuwaiti Actor Dawood Hussain Visits NYFA Abu Dhabi|last=Pasquine|first=Frank|date=2014-09-18|website=New York Film Academy Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>, called ''al-mubahila''. After that, he went to produce over sixty albums, consisting of seven to ten tracks each.<ref name=\":2\" /> He was also the first reciter to release a music video. In the late 1990's and early 2000s, he saw a huge success in album sales in [[Kuwait]], [[Bahrain]], [[Eastern Province, Saudi Arabia|Saudi]] and [[Lebanon]]. In 2003, after the Iraq invasion, when religious repression was lifted from the Shia's, religious songs became a sought for commodity. Music stores across the country would declare that in ordinary days, people would buy ten Basim [[Compact disc|CD's]] to one [[Kadim Al Sahir|Kadhim al-Sahir]] CD, as for during religious seasons, sales of Basim CD's would significantly increase.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Qari' Husayni Yakhtuf Qulub al-Ajyal al-Jadida|date=2005|work=al-Noor Magazine|access-date=|url-status=live|issue=57-58|language=ar|trans-title=Husayni reciter robs the hearts of the new generation}}</ref> Gradually, al-Karbalaei's media presence and following became huge, his [[YouTube|Youtube]] channel<ref>{{Citation|last=|first=|title=BasimKarbalaei Youtube Channel|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/bkstaff110|volume=|pages=}}</ref> began to show for this, with more than six million subscribers and just under two billion video views.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCLlMiPx_v5jFahvImDu_EFQ|title=Basim Karbalaei / \u0628\u0627\u0633\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0643\u0631\u0628\u0644\u0627\u0626\u064a|last=|first=|date=|website=YouTube|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27|quote=6.38M Subscribers. 1,986,939,273 views}}</ref>\n\nal-Karbalaei has appeared on numerous state television channels, such as Bahrain, Lebanon and Iraq, and his sound tracks are constantly aired. He frequently appears on satellite channels.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Haytham|first=Zafan|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=YjFOAQAAIAAJ|title=al-Fadha'iyat al-Shi'iya al-Tabshiriya|date=2010|publisher=Markaz al-Tanweer Lil Dirasat al-Insaniya|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=Shia Satellite Channels}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\nal-Karbalaei has authored three volumes of his book ''Hatha Ma Qara't'' (This Is What I Have Recited), which is a compilation of the elegies he has recited across his career.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Sheikh Ali|first=Abdul Qadir|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=rUY6AQAAIAAJ|title=al-Mowsooa al-Shi'riya al-Mahdawiya|date=2010|publisher=Dar al-Uloom Lil Tahqiq Wal Tibaa Wal Nashra Wal Tawzee|year=|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=|language=ar}}</ref>\n\n== Personal Life ==\nal-Karbalaei is married to an [[Omanis|Omani]] woman. He has four children, a son (Ali) and three daughters (Fatima, Rayhanah and Roghayeh).<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Kaabi|first=Ahmed|title=Basim al-Karbalai Safir al-Inshad al-Husayni|publisher=Maktabat Tareeq al-Ma'rifa|year=2010|isbn=|location=Cairo, Egypt|pages=120|trans-title=Basim Karbalaei: The Ambassador of Husayni Eulogies}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|last=al-Kaabi|first=Ahmed|url=|title=Munth Tufulati Wa Ana A'shaq Qira'at al-Qasa'id al-Hussainia|date=2010|work=Sawt al-Safir Newspaper|access-date=|url-status=live|language=ar|trans-title=Since My Childhood I Loved Reciting Husayni Elegies}}</ref> His daughter Fatima, participated in his album Sawad al-Layl, in 2007, while his son Ali and daughter Roghayeh, began participating in albums with their father in 2013 until 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zxYOEuFHAVA|title=Liqaa' al-Haj Basim al-Karbalaei|last=|first=|date=|website=YouTube|publisher=@BasimKarbalaei|language=ar|trans-title=Basim Karbalaei's Interview|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Muharram Participations ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Muharram Participation's\n![[Year|Gregorian Year]]\n![[Lunar calendar|Lunar Year]]\n!Organisation\n!Location\n!Highlight Eulogy\n<small>(Video on ''YouTube'')</small>\n|-\n|1988\n|1409\n|Masjid al-Imam al-Husayn\n|[[Qom]], [[Iran]]\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8908ASSSG18 ''Yikfi al-Hadhum Wil Nowh'']\n|-\n|1989\n|1410\n|al-Husayniya al-Zaynabiya\n|Qom, Iran\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PUhOT5Ey8SA ''Lo Ridit Husn al-Aqiba'']\n|-\n|1990\n|1411\n|Husayniat al-Imam Ali\n|[[Damascus]], [[Syria]]\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hqT6vPnfcrE ''Kilmen Yihasib Dhamira'']\n|-\n|1991\n|1412\n|al-Husayniya al-Zaynabiya\n|Qom, Iran\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kBYPGSjdCMw ''Goom Irwiha'']\n|-\n|1992\n|1413\n|al-Husayniya al-Zaynabiya\n|Qom, Iran\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fbTI__4Sj74 ''Ma Nidri Ya Walina'']\n|-\n|1993\n|1414\n|al-Husayniya al-Zaynabiya\n|Qom, Iran\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S_5y1HqDkI0 ''Mahla al-Wida' al-Yawm'']\n|-\n|1994\n|1415\n|Husayniyat al-Rasool al-Adham - al-Karbalaeia<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090314081233/http://www.alkarbalaeia.net/media/index.php?main_page=song&cPath=100_126&sPath=100|title=Haj Basim al-Karbalaei - Muharram 1415 AH|last=|first=|date=2009-03-14|website=alkarbalaeia.net|language=ar|via=web.archive.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-